column2: I want to collect unit test result by using hygieia-jenkins-plugin. How to set results directory and file name pattern in Publish Test Results. What plug-INS generate these files and file content?
column5: How to set results directory and file name pattern in Publish Test Results?
column12:
270120571 For unit tests, Hygieia expects the tests in Sonar. For functional tests that are cucumber/selenium based, you can use the hygieia-jenkins plugin option. Jenkins cucumber plugin generates the json files that are read by the hygieia plugin. tabladrum
270129306 

Thanks you reply. But I have a question:  Jenkins cucumber plugin can generate unit test result in json files? In general, cucumber is used for Behaviour-Driven Development. But I still do not understand why the cucumber can also be used to produce unit test results？ wangjianwen
270149925 Yes it can. As long as there is a json file the hygieia plugin should work.  tabladrum
270333709 Thanks you reply! I will try to install Jenkins cucumber plugin.  wangjianwen

column5: Deploy widget grouping is incorrect
column12:
270018620 After reading the thread, I think I follow... Would it make more sense for the collector to record the deployment server as a compound key? i.e. ```json [ { "applicationId": "MyTestApp", "deployServer": "TestJenkins" }, { "applicationId": "MySecondApp", "deployServer": "TestJenkins" }, { "applicationId": "AnotherTestApp", "deployServer": "TestJenkins" } ] ``` I'm not sure exactly what the data looks like that the widget is displaying or if I completely understand the problem, but this data model would make it possible to group/aggregate by deploy server, as proposed. mrpudn 270125129 @mrpudn changing the collectors / collector_items around would be a big undertaking and would most certainly not be backwards compatible. @tabladrum Looks fine so long as the same guid implies the same name (meaning we don't care about renaming). Just note I don't see the api endpoint I made going away as there are more uses for it. For example: Configurable Pipeline Stage Names #1020 MarkRx 270130185 @MarkRx The "System Config" API should evolve. For this particular instance we will rely on the UI config ability. tabladrum 270131578 Sounds good. MarkRx 270150077 https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/1055 tabladrum 269544000 Do the created collector items have unique options.applicationId's? Can you post them? The assumption would be that "MyTestApp", "MySecondApp", and "AnotherTestApp" would each have their own unique applicationId. If not then they will be treated as the same application if they all have the same instanceUrl (and thus assume they have the same application name for all 3 which is why the first name is used in the group) ``` var dataGrouped = dataGrouped = _(data) .groupBy(function(d) { return (!multiServerEquality ? d.options.instanceUrl + "#" : "" ) + d.options.applicationId; }) .map(function(d) { return d; }); ``` MarkRx 269547708 Ah. Got it. In my case (testing jenkins plugin) I had the same instanceUrl. And no applicationId in the collector item option. May be the workaround is to put Job url in the "instanceUrl". Not sure yet. But manually editing the json document to make the instance url the job url did work. Noticed that if I turn the grouping off, it still groups. tabladrum 269574464 @MarkRx the following code should work both ways: ``` var dataGrouped = _(data) .groupBy(function(d) { return (!multiServerEquality || d.options.applicationId == null ? d.options.instanceUrl + "#"+d.options.applicationName : "" ) + d.options.applicationId; }) .map(function(d) { return d; }); ``` Can you test this change locally? tabladrum 269631174 I think the proper solution should be to have the jenkins plugin assign each application an applicationId. That field really shouldn't be nullable as it is meant to be an identifier. The identifier could be something arbitrary like the md5sum of the instanceUrl + applicationName. It's possible there are other parts of the code that will choke if it is null. Since a.applicationId == b.applicationId implies a.applicationName == b.applicationName you can use this: ``` var dataGrouped = dataGrouped = _(data) .groupBy(function(d) { return (!multiServerEquality ? d.options.instanceUrl + "#" : "" ) + d.options.applicationName + "#" + d.options.applicationId; }) .map(function(d) { return d; }); ``` MarkRx 269642107 The origin of applicationID was from uDeploy that had some kind of of UUID for each applicationID. I am sure this ID will change if the same App was setup in another "Prod" uDeploy server. May be we should create another ID (some kind of CMDB identifier)? In your case, how are you keeping this ID same across multiple deployment server? tabladrum 269650311 I kind of "cheated". XLD uses composite path keys based on the names of items in the path. Since this is the case the applicationId remains the same so long as they have the same path. For example: Server1: Id: Applications/Foo/Bar Name: Bar Server2: Id: Applications/Foo/Bar Name: Bar MarkRx 269986021 @MarkRx @amitmawkin @satishc1 @mrpudn please review these following change proposal before I submit it in a PR form: With PR https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/891 there was a change in how deployed Apps were grouped together by "deploying server"s. Nice change. This allows to visualize an App deployment where different deployment servers (such as QA Jenkins, Prod Jenkins or whatever) are deploying the same app. There are two major changes in that PR: 1. New API for to return a boolean attribute (systemConfig.multipleDeploymentServers) to the API properties file that determines if servers need to be grouped. 2. UI changes to group the servers in https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/UI/src/components/widgets/deploy/config.js and https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/UI/src/components/widgets/deploy/config.html I am proposing a refactor of #1 and slight change to #2. **Slight Change to #2**: Instead of relying on non-null applicationId, I am proposing a non-null applicationName + applicationId check in grouping of elements: *Old code* (https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/UI/src/components/widgets/deploy/config.js) ``` var dataGrouped = _(data) .groupBy(function(d) { return (!multiServerEquality ? d.options.instanceUrl + "#" : "" ) + d.options.applicationId; }) .map(function(d) { return d; }); ``` *Proposed change* ``` var dataGrouped = _(data) .groupBy(function(d) { return (!multiServerEquality ? d.options.instanceUrl + "#" : "" ) + d.options.applicationName + d.options.applicationId; }) .map(function(d) { return d; }); ``` **Refactoring of #1** Instead of capturing/configuring the "multipleDeploymentServers" property via API, I am proposing that we do that in the UI and store each individual dashboard's choice in the "dashboard" document in dashboard -> widgets -> options section of the json document: ``` { "_id" : ObjectId("5863ed079220ab16e6a1c3c8"), "name" : "deploy", "componentId" : ObjectId("583394884969c83f6715b588"), "options" : { "id" : "deploy0", "aggregateServers" : true } }, ``` Corresponding UI changes are pretty simple. *Add a check box in deploy widget config:* ```
``` Add a new variables in the corresponding controller (config.js) and add a function that looks like this: ``` $scope.reload = function() { processResponse(ctrl.currentData); }; ``` And store the currentData in a global variable after the data is obtained from the API calls. With these changes, there will be no API needed to save/retrieve the config and the config is set for each individual dashboard. Thoughts? Screen shots: ![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/6014941/21591810/8f11a27e-d0d5-11e6-8e63-fecc76d3a1c2.png) ![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/6014941/21591823/af2b0668-d0d5-11e6-91e5-3463dcf2bc8c.png) ![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/6014941/21591826/bf23852c-d0d5-11e6-937f-f69b132f0a19.png) ![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/6014941/21591831/d4c68654-d0d5-11e6-8ced-6671732c4a7d.png) tabladrum 270018620 After reading the thread, I think I follow... Would it make more sense for the collector to record the deployment server as a compound key? i.e. ```json [ { "applicationId": "MyTestApp", "deployServer": "TestJenkins" }, { "applicationId": "MySecondApp", "deployServer": "TestJenkins" }, { "applicationId": "AnotherTestApp", "deployServer": "TestJenkins" } ] ``` I'm not sure exactly what the data looks like that the widget is displaying or if I completely understand the problem, but this data model would make it possible to group/aggregate by deploy server, as proposed. mrpudn 270125129 @mrpudn changing the collectors / collector_items around would be a big undertaking and would most certainly not be backwards compatible. @tabladrum Looks fine so long as the same guid implies the same name (meaning we don't care about renaming). Just note I don't see the api endpoint I made going away as there are more uses for it. For example: Configurable Pipeline Stage Names #1020 MarkRx 270130185 @MarkRx The "System Config" API should evolve. For this particular instance we will rely on the UI config ability. tabladrum 270131578 Sounds good. MarkRx 270150077 https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/1055 tabladrum

Do you offer any means to authenticate the collector so we can retrieve the data? Note that I do not want to federate the Hygieia Application it self, only the collectors (for now).

269467376 @tabladrum the point is when the request gets to the enterprise reverse proxy it identifies the call as an unauthenticated one, and redirects the call to the federation authentication page. Once this is a collector request, there is no user to provide credentials, and the request fails.  All this happens before the collector request reach the destination tool. I was wondering if it is possible to provide user credentials to the collectors, so it can use the credential when requesting data. mmullerbr

column2:
When having a large amount of collector items for a specific collector type (10000 Jenkins Jobs for instance), it could take some extra time to send all of the items to the UI. This pull request allows the api to return paginated results. We also repurposed the 'collectorItemsByType' operation to allow for a search/filter functionality. This is backwards compatible with all widgets and is a non breaking change; the only changes to the response from the API are in the header dictating paging information. If no paging information is included in the request, all items are returned by default.

We will have PR's in the future that allow these widgets to have a 'typeahead' functionality that will dynamically load the field as you type, which utilize the changes made in this PR. This will all result in a significant performance increase and enhance user experience in the case of large collector item sets.

268987955 @pxk5958 is actually investigating this right now. We also have 10000's of Jenkins jobs and the build widget config in-particular is not very responsive. We have found two causes:

- The angular module ui-select has several well known performance problems. @pxk5958 was looking into using an alternative called selectize.
- For some reason spring is taking a long time to serialize the database results into objects. Results return quickly when using a mongo utility.

Does paging really help? I don't think the actual network load is an issue. You might be seeing a perceived increase in performance because the reduction in data addresses reduces the effects of both issues above.

 MarkRx

column12:
268658328 How does the jenkins plugin handle multiple scms right now? Are we just using the first?

The metadata is needed. It wouldn't make sense for metadata to be a list as it is simply a key-value property holder (that corresponds to artifactory properties). Instead you could use a numbering scheme similar to how jenkins handles multiple repositories. Example:

```
scmUrl: "url",
scmUrl1: "url1",
scmUrl2: "url2"
scmBranch: "..."
scmBranch1: "..."
```

@pxk5958 did you encounter this with #1038? MarkRx
268661040 Currently it stores the SCMs in a list of CodeRepo structure. For most cases it is just one. Not sure if any one builds multiple repos at once. tabladrum

column2:
Since this has been the source of several issues, I think it best to disable browser-sync's [`ghostMode`](https://www.browsersync.io/docs/options/#option-ghostMode) feature, by default.

Ghost mode can be enabled by running `gulp serve:ghost-mode` if you require this functionality.

Resolves #1016

268311865 I resolved the issue.  Problem was in by .bowerrc file.  

I had following in the file:
```
{
  "directory": "library",
  "registry": "http://bower.herokuapp.com",
  "proxy": "[PROXY_SERVER_ADDRESS_:PORT_HERE]",
  "https-proxy": "[PROXY_SERVER_ADDRESS:PORT_HERE]"
}
```

When I changed to this:
```
{
  "proxy": "[PROXY_SERVER_ADDRESS_:PORT_HERE]",		
  "https-proxy": "[PROXY_SERVER_ADDRESS:PORT_HERE]"
}
```
It worked.

Thanks for pointing me in the right direction. Mark-Smithh
268323424 Ah, ok - glad to see you got it resolved.

As a side note - you shouldn't have to set the bower proxy settings explicitly like that. It should honor your `HTTP_PROXY` and `HTTPS_PROXY` environment variables, if you have them set. Most tools follow this convention, which makes things much easier behind a proxy. mrpudn

column2:
Adds support for Jenkins pipeline plugin. https://wiki.jenkins-ci.org/display/JENKINS/Pipeline+Plugin

Includes support for addons to the plugin such as the multi-branch pipeline. Child jobs show up as "parent/child". Note that a job will not show up without a build.

SVN was not tested but should work as there were no provider specific changes made.

column2: Problem: When the Jenkins collector runs and encounters a workflow type job ("_class":"org.jenkinsci.plugins.workflow.job.WorkflowRun"), the collector throws an exception since workflow type jobs don't have changeSets. This is a fix to add a null check and immediately exit from the method when there are no changeSets to build, but still allow to collect build information from a workflow job.
column5: changes to allow collecting builds from a workflow type jenkins job
column12:
267103536 Thanks @MarkRx  amitmawkin
267134415 Full support for jenkins pipeline plugin PR #1038 MarkRx
267160270 @amitmawkin this solves the error encountered on any workflow type job with just an addition of a null check. I probably should reword this request to instead say "handle null changeSet scenarios",
 which i happen to have encountered on workflow type jobs. Thanks. Mpluya
267167141 @Mpluya Workflow/Pipeline jobs have the changesets as a JSONArray of "changeSets" instead of "changeSet" in normal jobs. That's why you're encountering the NPE. With your change, it would skip the NPE, but will not collect the actual changesets if present. pxk5958
267204885 @pxk5958 I appreciate the explanation. Closing this request since PR #1038 addresses the entire need. Mpluya
267085723 @Mpluya Does this take care for Jenkins 2.0 pipelines too, or just the workflow plugin.  amitmawkin
267102203 @pxk5958 has a PR coming soon that will support the pipeline plugin MarkRx
267103536 Thanks @MarkRx  amitmawkin
267134415 Full support for jenkins pipeline plugin PR #1038 MarkRx
267160270 @amitmawkin this solves the error encountered on any workflow type job with just an addition of a null check. I probably should reword this request to instead say "handle null changeSet scenarios",
 which i happen to have encountered on workflow type jobs. Thanks. Mpluya
267167141 @Mpluya Workflow/Pipeline jobs have the changesets as a JSONArray of "changeSets" instead of "changeSet" in normal jobs. That's why you're encountering the NPE. With your change, it would skip the NPE, but will not collect the actual changesets if present. pxk5958
267204885 @pxk5958 I appreciate the explanation. Closing this request since PR #1038 addresses the entire need. Mpluya

Unfortunately, we still have a jira 5.1 instance running in the company with which I met a NullPointerException in Jira collector. I change the code locally to get it working with jira 5.1 api, currently.
Therefore, I am not sure do your team has the clear scope on what is the lowest supported version of Jira (mostly we're running 6+)?  

Plus to share the issue:
on the jira API  <jira-host>/rest/api/2/status: 
6.1+
```json
{
  "description": "The issue is open and ready for the assignee to start work on it.",
  "iconUrl": "http://xxx/images/icons/statuses/open.png",
  "id": "1",
  "name": "Open",
  "self": "http://xxx/rest/api/2/status/1",
  "statusCategory": {
    "colorName": "blue-gray",
    "id": 2,
    "key": "new",
    "name": "To Do",
    "self": "http://xxx/rest/api/2/statuscategory/2"
  }
}
```
5.1:
```json
{
  "description": "The issue is open and ready for the assignee to start work on it.",
  "iconUrl": "http://xxxx/images/icons/status_open.gif",
  "id": "1",
  "name": "Open",
  "self": "http://xxx/rest/api/2/status/1"
}
```
According to **Hygieia/collectors/feature/jira/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/client/DefaultJiraClient.java**, line [367-369]:
```java
Object statusCategory = jsonStatus.get("statusCategory");
JSONObject jsonStatusCategory = (JSONObject) statusCategory;
String statusCategoryName = (String) jsonStatusCategory.get("name");
```
Obviously, if I am running with jira 5.1 api, I will get a null statusCategory which leads to a NullPointerException when I afterwards try to get() from null :(

Currently I make the if statement after line 367 to judge with I get a null of 'statusCategory' to get everything working.

Please advice if you're support jira 5.1 .

Thanks,
Xiaopeng

column2:
Hi Team,
I am using the Hygieia Jenkins plugin to publish deployment details on Hygieia db but it is not clearly documented anywhere as how to and why to create different environments like Dev, Int, Perf in jenkins so that it will reflect on teams of Deploy widget configuration. Any clarification would be helpful. Thanks.
column5: No teams were found in Deploy widget of Hygieia db
column12:
268540175 @supremex1 You can create jobs in Jenkins that deploy to Dev , QA , Int , Perf , Prod.
In these jobs, under Post Build Actions -> Hygieia Publisher -> select "Publish Build Status" and  "Publish Deployment Results" and fill in the details of your artifact. The environment name will be set to one of Dev , QA , Int , Perf , Prod.  Then run these jobs and you should see the deploy widget populated. satishc1

Why I am seeing all the project in the list even though I have given one ID in the properties file:? Mahendra1260
268243855 There is no spot in the properties file to restrict to a specific project. The jira collector will gather all project names and provide them as a drop down. MarkRx

**_feature.jiraProjectId=MyProjectID_**

268521095 There is no field called feature.jiraProjectID. I do not know where that came from.

Jira does not have a user role system. The jira collector will pick up whatever the user has access to that is defined in the jira collector properties. Creating such a system is no small task and I don't see it being done any time soon if at all. MarkRx

column2: We have been looking into the security in Hygieia and have some concerns with how it’s implemented.  It looks like there is a call to the API service to login, but after that, all the authorization is in javascript and based on a couple cookies.  Security can be bypassed completely with very little effort.  Is there any work being done to address this? If not, we might look into improving this.

298747096 Sorry, that comment was in regards to @montapas , I haven't attempted to use ldaps, so it is possible, but I don't have a way to test it.  rob-miller-777
298747262 Probably better to open new issues for these questions instead of reusing this one. rob-miller-777
320539896 finallllllllly.  This was really painful guys. I have been pulling my hair out trying to figure out how to get the auth token for API.  Thought the API set up  info was outdated as I did not see any settings panel.  The API start up guide needs to mention 2 things: auth.authenticationProviders=STANDARD needs to be set to allow a user to be created....and on set up the user: admin needs to be created immediately.  I looked through the start up guides again and I do not see anything referencing these facts.  It would really help to have them stated in bold. htvan1
320540043 @satishc1 @Megha849 can you see this? tabladrum
320551684 Also I am now not sure if the API guide's section on Securing APIs Basic Auth...is correct even when I have the API token from the admin screen.  I tried those lines of code to encode the api token I got. Then added the user name and auth token in as headers... still got 401 unauthorized.  I suppose that would be a different ticket, but a full run though example in the guide would do wonders.   Thanks @tabladrum for helping me sort out the tribal knowledge in the API guide. htvan1
266487101 There is - from LDAP, OAUTh etc to API token based authentication.  tabladrum
266487195 But won't complain if you help :-) tabladrum
266488753 Yeah, @brennanananan has been working on integrating with ldap here.  I think the biggest issue we have found is that you can change a cookie value right now on the client and be any user you want to be.  We think we need to implement some sort of backend security to the api calls, which would probably mean utilizing spring security on the API.  rob-miller-777
266491902 We saw it too. It's on the list of things to look at. MarkRx
266504710 Currently the authentication from UI etc was there to only support personalization of dashboards.
All dashboard's are inherently in a read only mode, but can only be edit by the owner of those dashboards,
We need JWT for the API layer, and modify the auth to move from cookie mode to sending JWT tokens with each api request, when ever somebody login they will get a temp token that they need to send with each api request.  amitmawkin
266531813 Sounds good, @brennanananan and I are looking into implementing JWT.   rob-miller-777
266795130 It might be nice to add GitHub OAuth as a near-term SSO goal. LDAP can be heavy. mrpudn
270969656 Hey guys, just wanted to provide an update.  @brennanananan and I have put a lot of work into implementing security, and we are getting close to having it where we want.  From a users perspective, almost nothing has changed.  But the application is secure from the backend now.

**What we have done so far**
- Implemented JWT to provide stateless authentication/authorization
- Updated angular client to work with JWT tokens
- Made token expiration configurable
- Implemented redirect functionality to take you to the page you were viewing if you token expires and you have to login again
- Made secret key configurable to support having multiple instances of the API running
- Added Spring Security to Rest API
- Built in support for multiple forms of authentication (only standard Hygieia Auth implemented at this point, but adding others should be easy)
- Refactored current login to work with Spring Security
- Created a UserInfo Repository separate from the Authentication repository to support multiple forms of authentication.  This lets us control all application specific details of a user such as roles and themes independent of the authentication type. (Themes are still only handled by the angular app on the client, and saved in local storage, but this is something we can now save for a user if we want to)
- Made admin a "role" instead of just assigning admin privileges to the user named "admin". (Haven't implemented a way to assign new admins yet, so right now it works as before where the user named "admin" is given the role of admin)
- Added method level security to dashboard modification controller so only owners of the dashboard or admins can modify a dashboard
- Added support for having multiple owners of a dashboard (have not created anyway to assign multiple owners yet, but shouldn't be hard to do)
- Implemented new owner functionality in such a way that it won't break backwards compatibility

**What we have left**

- Clean up and refactor code
- Add and update some unit tests
- Document what we have done and how things work
- Document how to add additional forms of authentication (oauth, ldap, etc...)

Here is a link to the diff if you want to take a look at what we have so far: https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/compare/master...StateFarmIns:springSecurityIntegration

Let us know if you have any questions or concerns on what we have, should have a pull request coming shortly.  
 rob-miller-777
272003768 Do you guys think you should have to be authenticated to view dashboards?  Or should you be able to view dashboards without logging in? rob-miller-777
272004379 You should be able to share a dashboard with anybody, irrespective of having an account or not.
  amitmawkin
272174216 Not sure I agree. I think it should be configurable if the "anonymous" user has view access. If Hygieia runs enterprise wide I'm not sure I want anyone in the company being able to see it. MarkRx
272175081 We started with a "100% transparent" dashboard mindset. Works for us very well. But I do realize that this may not fit in other organizations.  tabladrum
272210863 We will implemented with the "100% transparent" dashboard mindset, and it might be worth adding some functionality around private dashboards in the future.   rob-miller-777

275693699 To be able to utilize LDAP, you have to have configured the API to utilize your ldap server.  Which means providing the url to the LDAP server, and the DN string.  Without both of these present, the LDAP authentication provider will not be created.  The properties can be found in the README for the api.   rob-miller-777

276388451 The "attemptAuthentication" method in the LdapLoginRequestFilter is responsible for pulling the username and password out of the request, and creating a "UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken" which will be handled by Spring Securities built in LDAP authentication provider.  From the issues you are having it seems like there are probably two potential issues you could be facing.  The first would be an improperly configured ldap server, most likely your DN string not being accurate.  The other possibility would be you are entering the wrong username/password combination on the login page.  I imagine both could give you the Bad Credential error.   rob-miller-777

Regarding your second comment, If you don't select your particular team, it'll aggregate data from other teams in your project, so that's why it shows the points. pxk5958

Even though if I select all teams.. the widgets shows me all 0's. Not sure of what exactly it is happening.. but need a clear understanding of this widget..
 vishnuvangala
268522270 To show scrum sprints you must (1) have the collector property configured, and (2) have a project/team have an active ending sprint. If a sprint exists but has no end date it will be treated as a kanban sprint.
@vishnuvangala as is the case with most of the jira issues reported here the cause has been the jira collector not being correctly configured. Note that if you make a change to the collector config the change will only apply to newly collected jira items. Hence, you may need to wipe your jira data and recollect it.

sEstimate comes from the story point estimates that are put on stories. sEstimateTime comes from time estimates that are put on subtasks of stories. Hours estimates for tasks keep track of the total estimate and how much time has been put into the issue. From these open, wip, and done values can be deduced.

@Mahendra1260 double check your configuration. Note that if a sprint is not active (start date <= now <=(?) end date) it will not show up. If you do not select any team than "Any team" is assumed. MarkRx
277277346 @vishnuvangala The feature widget now has an option to display metrics based on the number of tickets instead of estimates. This is for setups that do not use estimates.
Functionality merged in https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/1054 Use latest codebase. You’ll also need to follow cleanup instructions provided in https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/1137 satishc1

```properties
feature.jiraIssueTypeNames=Story

```

268522270 To show scrum sprints you must (1) have the collector property configured, and (2) have a project/team have an active ending sprint. If a sprint exists but has no end date it will be treated as a kanban sprint.
@vishnuvangala as is the case with most of the jira issues reported here the cause has been the jira collector not being correctly configured. Note that if you make a change to the collector config the change will only apply to newly collected jira items. Hence, you may need to wipe your jira data and recollect it.

sEstimate comes from the story point estimates that are put on stories. sEstimateTime comes from time estimates that are put on subtasks of stories. Hours estimates for tasks keep track of the total estimate and how much time has been put into the issue. From these open, wip, and done values can be deduced.

@Mahendra1260 double check your configuration. Note that if a sprint is not active (start date <= now <=(?) end date) it will not show up. If you do not select any team than "Any team" is assumed. MarkRx
277277346 @vishnuvangala The feature widget now has an option to display metrics based on the number of tickets instead of estimates. This is for setups that do not use estimates.
Functionality merged in https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/1054 Use latest codebase. You’ll also need to follow cleanup instructions provided in https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/1137 satishc1

Updated Angular version to latest stable release of Angular (1.5.9), as well as updated version of UI-Bootstrap (2.3.0).  

Most of the changes that had to be made outside of the version changes revolved around Angular Bootstrap, and Angular Cookies. The bootstrap dependency started prefixing their modules with "uib", which accounts for a significant portion of the changes. Angular changed their cookie api to use "getters" and "puts" instead of accessing the variables directly.
column5: Angular/UI-Bootstrap Update to latest

266965934 Thanks @rob-miller-777 ,
    One quick question regarding git-lab is.. I dont see the widget getting updated automatically.. we are performing some commits on project and I have set the cron job property as 1min in my git-lab.properties file. But still I dont see them updated in widget.. Unless I click on edit and click on save.. then I'm able to see the updated results there.. any idea? vishnuvangala
267046759 If you refresh the page, do you see the new data?  The dashboard and the collector are on different timers.  So even if the collector retrieves new data, you won't see it on the dashboard until the dashboard refreshes what it has by calling the UI.  If you don't see the data when you refresh the page, but you do see it when you update the configuration of the widget, my guess would be that you are running into a bug I found.  It seems like there is an issue with all widgets where if you have the same widget running for the same data on multiple dashboards, and one dashboard is either deleted, or removes that widget, it will disable that widget on all dashboards that widget is on.  So for example in Gitlab, if DashboardA and DashboardB both have an SCM widget looking at GitlabRepo1.  If DashboardB is either deleted, or changes that widget to look at GitlabRepo2, it will also disable it for DashboardA.   rob-miller-777

column2: Fixes the dashboard sometimes not showing data right away due to a timing issue. I think it has to do with the order the asynchronous rest calls come back in. This wraps the setTeamData method into a $timeout function which puts it at the end of the event queue and causes a $scope.$apply() to be run after it is finished. I don't know if the $timeout wrap is necessary (as opposed to using $scope.$apply() but that is what other js functions do so I followed suit.

column2:
Added configurable pipeline stage names. Backwards compatible. Allows for more and different stage names. Also allows users to hide the Commit and Build stages.

Stage config defaults to:

> systemConfig.systemStages=${CONFIG_GLOBAL_SYSTEM_STAGES:-Commit,Build,DEV,QA,INT,PERF,PROD}

Assumptions:
- There is at most one "commit" stage and one "build" stage
- Users will not have more than 9 stages including build/commit (the UI column widths are not dynamic due to grids and I didn't see a need to make it dynamic)

![feature1100-2](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/17504314/20983884/21f0385c-bc8c-11e6-8dcd-6511a7c74e13.PNG)

![feature1100-3](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/17504314/20983890/282ebd06-bc8c-11e6-89b0-c5e169229f90.PNG)

![feature1100-4_2](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/17504314/20984086/e1412a04-bc8c-11e6-9c53-4c4b80d909e5.png)
column5: Configurable Pipeline Stage Names
column12: 278775942 Will try tomorrow. Thanks! MarkRx 279045840 I see a number of issues: - There are lingering references and logic referring to the System stages in the api settings. If any arbitrary stage can be created (as it seems is this case with the changes) then these need to be removed. If not then the UI needs to be tightened to make names of stages aliases to set system stages. - There needs to be a way of having deterministic ordering on environment stages. This is needed in pipeline computations (such as finding the last stage a pipeline was in). If the intent is to remove the set global system stages then you will have to store ordering in the widget. The code as it is right now is not going to properly compute pipeline metrics (the mappings map in the widget has no intrinsic ordering). You should not rely on using a specific implementation (LinkedHashMap) - I don't think getCommitsAfterStage was modified correctly. - My product dashboard is still computing based on the system stages set. If the intent is for any team to have any arbitrary stages then this needs to have some kind of computation to determine the stages to display MarkRx 282108959 @MarkRx - I pushed latest changes to branch https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/tree/pr-1020 . -> Removed instances of api systemConfig. -> Used the ordering for stages in sequence they are added. Used the same order to display on Product dashboard. Check it out and let me know if you see issues. nireeshT 292325763 @MarkRx @nireeshT @tabladrum Bumping this thread. Badly needed feature for us. Can you please confirm is there is any plan to test the merged changes and make it part of main release. fluidjeel 292540953 @fluidjeel - this is merged to master. This PR creates a POST endpoint within the API that receives the data from Rundeck and creates an `EnvironmentComponent`.  The basic structure is a transformation from the Rundeck XML document that is provided to a `DeployDataCreateRequest` object, which can be passed into the existing create method.

This is dependent on existing PRs: #1005 and #1007 which are still under discussion.  I wanted to make this available so it could be reviewed and changes could be pushed up.

This is not a complete resolution for #1008 as I am working on a completely separate collector spring boot application that will be more flexible than this implementation.

column2:
When we serve the UI with gulp serve (without nginx), the interaction synchronization through [ghostMode](https://www.browsersync.io/docs/options#option-ghostMode) option causes problems. It is not working as intended and browsers end up in different pages sometimes and cause problems during testing. For example, we consistently end up in a scenario where one browser goes into a dashboard page whereas another browser remains in the home page (site.html), and eventually interactions trigger the deleteDashboard() javascript function on the latter browser. We consistently get a dashboard deleted when the Monitor widget's configure wheel button is clicked in the first browser. That is not the only case where dashboards get deleted though.

So the question is, was ghostMode intended to be used? If not, we could turn it off in gulpfile.js when initializing browser-sync, since it's causing the dashboards to be deleted during testing, which is rather annoying.

Other issues reporting similar problems: [#871](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/871), [#627](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/627)

@mrpudn @amitmawkin @tabladrum
column5: Is BrowserSync ghostMode necessary?
column12:
265355983 `ghostMode` can be useful if you're demonstrating something with a teammate or something, but I agree that this functionality could be provided via a separate command (i.e. `npm run develop` or `gulp develop`) and turned off by default.

I don't think this would be terribly hard to implement, and changing the default behavior of `gulp serve` should be transparent to users. mrpudn
268127617 @mrpudn currently how to start Hygieia instance from gulp without ghost mode ? xpdable
268284806 I just created a PR to address this issue.

If it gets merged, ghost mode will be disabled, by default. To enable it, you will be able to run `gulp serve:ghost-mode`. mrpudn

I have been working on a Rundeck collector which creates EnvironmentComponent deploy records.  I have a couple questions about the implementation:

1. I could use the Rundeck post-completion webhook to send records to a collector or build a collector from the API to run on a cron schedule, as the Github collector does. Is there a preferred approach?  Could I build the Rundeck post-completion webhook feature into the api itself, while also building a separate collector that runs on a cron schedule?
2. When building separate collectors, is it preferred to use the api endpoints to create mongo objects or do the collectors generally have their own `Repository` bean with a connection to the mongo db directly?

I created two PRs that I will be depending on for the implementation #1007 and #1005.  If these are not yet resolved, I would ask that we begin discussion there and then talk about the implementation here.

Adding #785 for reference.

column2:
The deployment POST endpoint does not align with the way that the data is displayed in a number of ways:

1. The jobUrl property is completely ignored (search for references to  DeployDataCreateRequest::getJobUrl() in IDE).  There should be an option to access the job URL component by component.
2. The `appName`/`instanceUrl` property pair is being defined as distinct in the backend [here](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/api/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/service/DeployServiceImpl.java#L242) because the query looks to match the options passed in.  This means that two collectors can be created with the same name, which then appears as the same name in the Deploy widget dropdown.
3. The environmentUrl doesn't get set in the [createEnvComponent](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/api/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/service/DeployServiceImpl.java#L248) method.  This means that jobs submitted by the POST endpoint do not have a functional "View in Jenkins" link, as this is captured by the `environment.url` property [here](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/UI/src/components/widgets/deploy/detail.html#L25)

My suggested solution:
1. `jobUrl` property gets set on the environment_component collection object, then if this value is set it is used by the [deploy detail modal](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/UI/src/components/widgets/deploy/detail.html).  It will need to be at the component level, as the `jobUrl` property is specifying a deploy URL for a component.
2. Make `applicationName` distinct in the CollectorItem repo by removing `option.put("instanceUrl", request.getInstanceUrl());` from [DeployServiceImpl.java](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/api/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/service/DeployServiceImpl.java).  I realize this would be a breaking change for those with duplicate records here already by `applicationName` and `instanceUrl`.  I don't know what the project stance on this issue would be.
3. The `environmentUrl` should be set by the `instanceUrl` that is available in the API object.

I will be creating a PR for the related issues above.  I wanted the issue created to begin a discussion on these solutions.
column5: Deployment API endpoint does not create deployments that display properly
column12:
264688063 Issue 2 becomes especially clear in the code when you look at the `hashCode` and `equals` methods for [`Environment.java`](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/api/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/model/deploy/Environment.java).  The URL is not taken into account when comparing these environments for equality. jmcshane
264971865 > Make applicationName distinct in the CollectorItem repo by removing option.put("instanceUrl", request.getInstanceUrl()); from DeployServiceImpl.java. I realize this would be a breaking change for those with duplicate records here already by applicationName and instanceUrl. I don't know what the project stance on this issue would be.

This will not work in all cases. It is perfectly valid to have the same application name on different instances and these would in turn be different logical items.  MarkRx
264982903 @MarkRx Then the `Environment.java` file needs to change as well as the view for choosing Deployment collectors, as right now the instanceUrl is not included in the display for choosing the collector.  The environment being tested for equality based only on the `appName` property means that I cannot create a map keyed on the `Environment` when there are two records with the same app name.

If you have another solution that allows these multiple instanceUrls in a way that makes it easy to work with, I'm definitely interested in working through this.  We could set a time to discuss on the gitter chat for this project if you are interested. jmcshane
264984105 Let me review this tonight.  tabladrum
264990206 > If you have another solution that allows these multiple instanceUrls in a way that makes it easy to work with, I'm definitely interested in working through this. We could set a time to discuss on the gitter chat for this project if you are interested.

What are you trying to accomplish? If you have the same application spread vertically across different instances (instances meaning deployment tools) look at #891.

In the collector model there is a single collector that defines N number of URLs and niceNames. Each collectorItem refers to the collector and has applicationName, instanceUrl (in options) and 'niceName' set. If the collectorItem has 'niceName' set the UI will differentiate entries using that.

If you send in niceName through the rest endpoint it should differentiate items in the UI for you. Look at https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/891#issuecomment-260472065 for an example. Doing so would allow you to be able to distinguish between two applications with the same name.


 MarkRx

column5: MongoDB Authentication exception while running api using docker
column12:
264270745 @vishnuvangala 
I also encountered the same issue and solve to follow below steps: 
1. Point mongoDb directory:
    ```
    mongod --dbpath < path to the data directory>
    ```
2. Create database 
    ```
    mongo
    MongoDB shell version: 3.0.4
    connecting to: test  
    > use dashboarddb
    switched to db dashboarddb 
    > db.createUser({
        user: "dashboarduser",
        pwd: "dbpassword",
        roles: [
          { role: "readWrite", db: "dashboard" }
        ]
      })
    ```
    Output similar to below should be seen in your mongo shell
    ```  
    Successfully added user: {
      "user" : "dashboarduser",
      "roles" : [
        {
          "role" : "readWrite",
          "db" : "dashboard"
        }
      ]
    }
    ```
3. Give DB credentials and port properly in you dashboard.properties then
    ```
    java -jar api.jar --spring.config.location=dashboard.properties
    ``` elangesk
264386166 @vishnuvangala @elangesk 
If you use dashboarddb then the role would be
```js
{ role: "readWrite", db: "dashboarddb" }
```
instead of 
```js
{ role: "readWrite", db: "dashboard" } 
```
And the corresponding properties file should have
```properties
dbname=dashboarddb
dbusername=dashboarduser
dbpassword=dbpassword
``` satishc1
264418112 Thanks @elangesk @satishc1 ,
Finally I could resolve this authentication issue but unable to access the api even after starting with below command.. not sure what went wrong.. but able to authenticate successfully with below command... 
But I have a quick question...
In order to setup Hygieia, should I run API, UI and mongoDB mandatorly in docker container? or can I also start with normal commands instead of running in docker container? Please suggest. I see some difficulty while running through docker and even in setting up this HYGIEIA.. if someone could help me in setting up through chat/live.. that would be great.

**Modified command used to run api using docker which resolved the mongo authentication issue:**
```
docker run \
  -t \
  -p 8082:8082 \
  -v /logs:/hygieia/logs \
  -e "SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_HOST=192.168.XX.XXX" \
  -e "SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PORT=27017" \
  -e "SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_DATABASE=dashboarddb" \
  -e "SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_USERNAME=dashboarduser" \
  -e "SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PASSWORD=dbpassword" \
  -i hygieia-api:latest
``` vishnuvangala
264724930 Glad to see your issue is resolved.

Docker is not required in order to run Hygieia - please see the setup instructions for the respective layer of Hygieia that you are trying to run:
https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/Setup.md

ie. for the API layer, you should be able to do:
```bash
mvn install
java -jar api.jar --spring.config.location=dashboard.properties
``` mrpudn
264774808 @mrpudn,
Yeah.. I understood that Docker is not mandatory after reviewing the document again. Looks like the setup document was messedup and confusing for the beginners who setup HYGIEIA.

Seriously, it was so simple to setup.. now, Im encountering with a different issue.. Unable to login to portal.. running the api on 8082 port.. looks like Im missing something.. If required I will raise a different issue.

Regards,
Vishnu vishnuvangala

264259362 What about all of the collectors? MarkRx
264263826 @MarkRx good question. So as far as the collectors that we're using go, the property that requires encryption is the database password.
Since the API's Docker file defines ENV SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PASSWORD, that is what's been encrypted. This env variable then gets picked up by the other collectors through the docker link to the API via $HYGIEIA_API_ENV_SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PASSWORD.

Let me know if you mean something else. Thanks! Mpluya
264756111 I am very interested in this feature as well and would want it to be available for all Spring Boot apps within the project.  I think with what @Mpluya has provided (with the jasypt library as a core dependency), the `@EnableEncryptableProperties` just needs to be added to each collector.

The argument `jasypt.encryptor.password` can be provided in the `spring.config.location` property file, so it can be called out along with the other configuration parameters in each of the collector `README.md` files.  Then, there would not be a need to have updates to any of the Dockerfiles as it just sits with the other properties. jmcshane
264759834 @Mpluya I created a PR to your project in StateFarmIns to add these properties and a callout in each section of the README documentation, see StateFarmIns/Hygieia#4 jmcshane
264867297 @jmcshane you are correct.  Enabling property encryption on the collectors is just a matter of adding the @EnableEncryptableProperties annotation to the Application class on each collector. I did not add it by default to all the collectors, since I would like property encryption to be added on an as needed basis. I don't want an additional post processor kicking off on startup of each collector if there are no encrypted properties to deal with. I'm open to having it turned on on every collector if thats what we all agree to do. 

As for your pull request, I really appreciate you taking the time to enable property encryption on all collectors. I'd like for folks to weigh in before we put this in. 
As for putting the secret key (jasypt.encryptor.password) as another property, I would have to disagree with this approach. I would prefer for the secret key to be passed in either as a system property or environment variable when starting up your spring boot app. In my opinion, having an encrypted property and next to it is the secret key - pretty much gives away the the decrypted value. That said, in my organization when we startup Hygieia via docker containers, the secret key gets served up from a secure variable in our gitlab ci runner. 

I look forward to hear your thoughts on this. Thank you again. Mpluya
264896583 @Mpluya after thinking this over a little more, you are definitely right about not having the `jasypt.encryptor.password` property in the property file itself.

I think we just need to call this out explicitly in each of the `README.md` files and then, as you say, update the `Dockerfile` for each collector.

I'll make a modification to the PR I sent to remove the callout of the password in the properties and modify the above documentation section to talk about the system property.
 jmcshane

column2:
Currently the Hygieia pipeline is hard coded to use at most 5 stages in the order of DEV > QA > INT > PERF > PROD. We have found that this approach does not satisfy all pipelines. 

I propose the following enhancements:

- (A) Custom stage names with a configurable number of system level stages. Some teams may use more than one level of integration environments. So the pipeline would become DEV > QA > INT1 > INT2 > PERF > PROD
- ~~(B) Configurable order of stages - Some teams use different staging orders. For example PERF testing might come at different locations in the pipeline.~~ System stage groups should be generic enough to work for all teams. I think keeping order consistent will simplify aggregation and metrics a bunch.
- (C) Multiple environments per stage - There may be parallel environments within a stage. For example, suppose there are 3 independent QA environments - qa1, qa2, and qa3. Components may go to any QA in any order. They must go to at least one QA before moving to a higher environment.

(A) is simply a matter of refactoring and adding functionality. (B) and (C) add flexibility at the cost of complexity.

Each team dashboard would be able to define which system level stages to use ~~along with the order that they are used in their pipeline~~. Grouping would also be definable so that N number of environments may be part of the same stage. The UI would have to be updated to display this information.

Product dashboards would have to change to take into account multiple environments per stage. In the case of a team having multiple environments per a stage the earliest date a PipelineCommit is seen in any of the environments in the stage would be used for calculations. 

## Examples
Given a system stage config of DEV, QA, INT1, INT2, PERF, PROD:

| Pipeline | DEV | QA            | INT1 | INT2 | PERF | PROD |
|----------|------|------------|-------|------|-------|--------|
| APP A   | dev1 | qa1 | int-a  | int-main | p1 | prod |
| APP B   | dev1 | qa1 / qa2 | int-a  | int-main | p2 | prod |
| APP C   |         | qa1 |   | int-main | p2 | prod |

Observe that App B has multiple parallel environments defined for the 'QA' stage.

Hygieia api's log gets stored in ./logs directory whereas the collectors' logs are created in the current directory itself. This inconsistency of log paths is present in src/main/resources/logback.xml

Api's logback.xml:
```xml
<fileNamePattern>logs/devopsdashboard-api-%d{yyyy-MM-dd}.%i.log</fileNamePattern>
```

Jira and other collectors' logback.xml:
```xml
<fileNamePattern>jiracollector-%d{yyyy-MM-dd}.%i.log</fileNamePattern>
```

column2:
Changes:

- Allow for configurable custom artifact formats using regex
- Adds modules, classifiers, and extensions to BinaryArtifacts to make them maven and ivy compliant.
- Artifacts published by jenkins no longer include the file extension as part of the artifact name. Instead the value is stored in the artifactExtension field.

Default artifact formats in documentation:
```
# Matches maven artifacts of the form [org]/[module]/[version]/[module]-[version]([-classifier])(.[ext])
artifactory.patterns[0]=(?<group>.+)/(?<module>[^/]+)/(?<version>[^/]+)/(?<artifact>\\k<module>)-\\k<version>(-(?<classifier>[^\\.]+))?(\\.(?<ext>.+))?
# Matches ivy files of the form [org]/[module]/[revision]/ivy-[revision](-[classifier]).xml 
artifactory.patterns[1]=(?<group>.+)/(?<module>[^/]+)/(?<version>[^/]+)/(?<artifact>ivy)-\\k<version>(-(?<classifier>[^\\.]+))?\\.(?<ext>xml)
# Matches ivy artifact files of the form [org]/[module]/[revision]/[type]/[artifact]-[revision](-[classifier])(.[ext])
artifactory.patterns[2]=(?<group>.+)/(?<module>[^/]+)/(?<version>[^/]+)/(?<type>[^/]+)/(?<artifact>[^\\.-/]+)-\\k<version>(-(?<classifier>[^\\.]+))?(\\.(?<ext>.+))?
```

Notes:

- Jenkins collector does not support maven classifiers at this time

Hi! 

I need to generate the Jenkins plugin and the plugin should be compiled with the same version of Java that Jenkins is using, in my case java7, but the plugin depends of the “core” project of Hygieia and it uses some features that are only present in Java 8 ( Lamda functions ).
So, there is a way to compile or generate jenkins plugin to run in java7 or just it won't work? 

Thank you!
column5: Build broken in Jenkins plugin with java7 due core dependency
column12:
263269266 Hygieia requires java 8. You could always run jenkins with a java 8 runtime and see if it functions properly.

Technically you could make a java 7 build by removing the CommitEventListener class as it seems to be the only item in core that requires java 8 features. No guarantees it will work as dependent libraries may require java 8 as well.
 MarkRx

I'll try to test in some other instance of Jenkins but it'll requiere a license (It's the cloudbee version) ...
Thanks anyway for your time :)

Regards, mqglobant

column2:
Contains a number of jira and feature collector / widget changes rolled up into a single PR from @pxk5958 

Changes:

- Jira collector now supports gathering team data. In the past Jira projects were being placed into 'scope' and 'ScopeOwner' (in collector_items). Now if the tempo team field is configured in the collector the team data is placed in 'ScopeOwner'. 
- Feature widget can filter based on project name, team name, or both. To grab all items for a given field / team the 'Any' option can be selected in the drop down.
- Feature widget can be configured to list Epics (previously called 'features') or Issues (stories, defects, spikes, etc).
- Added hyperlinks to epics / issues in progress
- Added hyperlink to sprint in progress
- Issues that have been completed now have a strikethrough on the UI
- Issues are sorted by modified date. Epics are still sorted by points. We feel that when listing stories a user will be more interested in recent activity.
- Feature widget modified to display open / in progress / done estimate metrics instead of total / in progress / done as this seems to be more intuitive.
- Added the ability to collect data on multiple issues types in the Jira collector
- Improved documentation / configuration of jira collector - renamed 'feature.jiraIssueTypeId' to 'feature.jiraIssueTypeNames'

Note: the feature collection will have to be wiped / reset in order to take advantage of urls and teams

The jira collector items that correspond to scopeowners will have to be wiped as they currently store project information

@tabladrum @amitmawkin we need to know how to construct urls to versionone assets in order to have hyperlinks be available for the version one feature.

![feature1](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/17504314/20573960/4f8abff6-b180-11e6-8ee9-53a65c163103.png)

![feature2](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/17504314/20573965/545aca3a-b180-11e6-9e9f-6423b1681e5c.png)

column2:
Our organization has a requirement to not store credentials (i.e. database credentials) in plaintext on the property files.
I noticed the codebase already has support for encrypt/decrypt by using the Encryption class on the core project.
The only downside in my opinion is I now have to add code to call the encryption class. It would be nice if my encypted properties are served up automatically decrypted.
That said, I found jasypt-spring-boot (Jasypt integration for Spring boot). It boot straps a Spring post processor which makes the app aware of the encrypted properties. Details about jasypt-spring-boot is here https://github.com/ulisesbocchio/jasypt-spring-boot.




My question is, would there be any interest in incorporating this in Hygieia?

column12:
262286026 Also if possible, can I have step by step installation documentation.  Mahendra1260
264726438 Docker is not required in order to run Hygieia.

For example, to install and start the API:
```bash
mvn install
java -jar api.jar --spring.config.location=dashboard.properties
```
I've been able to get Hygieia running on Linux following the same [Setup instructions](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/Setup.md).

If you encounter a specific error while trying to install and run the project on Linux, please feel free to open a new issue with logs and a description of your problem.

Thanks! mrpudn

column2:
Currently the Hygieia product allows users to create accounts, and then stores the passwords to those accounts in Mongo. This PR adds a new authentication service that can be used for LDAP based authentication to gain access to Hygieia. It uses an existing LDAP server implemeted by the deploying organization to check if an account merely exists. It has not been tested against group level access, but by modifying the dn in the application.properties file, more fine-grain restrictions should be able to be enforced (see README).

LDAP authentication can be activated through the "ldapAuth" spring profile, and setup instructions have been added to the api README.

263643735 @tabladrum I agree with the comments that @MarkRx supplied, however I currently do not have the bandwidth to work on them. It would be possible to change the authentication service dynamically based on the user trying to authenticate, but it might make more sense to hold off on the ldap integration until someone is able to implement role based access on top of what I have provided. brennanananan

261328035 Tests all pass when ran locally against the ldapIntegration2 branch after merging in master changes. Please advise.
 brennanananan
261375318 How do you login as an admin?

How does one turn this on or off using configuration in the docker files and docker-compose?
 MarkRx
261376738 I was unaware of there being admin functionality without these changes. Based on that assumption, this was not designed to support admin users.
To run with LDAP, the Dockerfile CMD for the API would be changed to say
`java -jar ....... --spring.profiles.active=ldapAuth` 

Running without LDAP is the default behavior.
 brennanananan
261376826 @brennanananan build failed. I manually restarted it. Let's see.
 tabladrum
261381088 @brennanananan build passed. magic! :-)
 tabladrum
261381222 @amitmawkin @satishc1 @MarkRx for review.
 tabladrum
261382466 @brennanananan undocumented feature, if you create a user with name admin you get to see an extra gear on the right top hand corner  that allows you to delete any dashboard and set themes.
 amitmawkin
261384839 Thanks @amitmawkin , I will take a look at how to incorporate that feature into my changes. Does the admin 'group' only get those two extra actions?
 brennanananan
261411293 Also, it seems you're assuming the usernames will be stored under uid. It may not be so and needs to be configurable as a search filter.

[Referrals](http://docs.oracle.com/javase/jndi/tutorial/ldap/referral/jndi.html) also need to be handled.

I encountered these issues with my organization's LDAP when working on this.
 pxk5958
261556709 - You need to change the docker properties builder so that no rebuild is necessary to be able to use LDAP
- The "sign up" feature needs to be hidden if ldap is enabled
- The "sign up" api call needs to throw an exception if ldap is enabled
- I would prefer reusing the existing auth controller and just checking a property dynamically to see if LDAP is enabled instead of using a spring profile. You can stick it into the systemConfig property map for now that is part of API. In the future we may want to build a System Config UI that can change these values and store them into the database. Using spring profiles prevents dynamic property changes without a restart.
- For now as a work around if the username is "admin" log in using the old mechanism. If not use ldap. A admin entry would have to be created in the database manually since the signup will be disabled if ldap is enabled (or create the admin user first then disable ldap). User roles could be added in the future.
 MarkRx

It would be possible to change the authentication service dynamically based on the user trying to authenticate, but it might make more sense to hold off on the ldap integration until someone is able to implement role based access on top of what I have provided. brennanananan

Advanced thanks.

column2:
Currently Does not support Proxy configuration - For Proxy add the -D flags while starting API.
This is still debatable whether we should save proxy credentials in Hygieia. We are discussing more internally before we enable proxy configuration.

Also currently the duration on which the API's are tested is every minute, in future we will make this configurable too.

More details about this can be read from features.md file.

This is still a WIP, we will be adding some more configuration and capabilities to this

261061307 @MarkRx  sorry I had to delete the Previous PR. Can you please review this one , I have your previous comments below

In api/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/service/ServiceServiceImpl.java:

> -        Service service = get(serviceId);
> -        LOGGER.info("URL is :" + service.getUrl());
> -        ServiceStatus status = getServiceStatusBasedOnHttpReturnCode(getHttpCode(service.getUrl()));
> -        service.setDashboardId(dashboardId);
> -        service.setStatus(status);
> -        service.setLastUpdated(System.currentTimeMillis());
> -        Dashboard dashboard = dashboardRepository.findOne(dashboardId);
> -        service.setApplicationName(dashboard.getApplication().getName());
> -        serviceRepository.save(service);
> -    }
>   +
> -    private ServiceStatus getServiceStatusBasedOnHttpReturnCode(int code) {
> -        ServiceStatus status = null;
> -        if (code == 200) {
> -            status = ServiceStatus.Ok;
> -        } else if (code >= 300 && code <= 400) {
>   Should be code < 400?
>   Also I think something should be logged

In pom.xml:

> @@ -220,6 +220,7 @@
>          <module>collectors/scm/github</module>
>          <module>collectors/scm/subversion</module>
>          <module>collectors/scm/gitlab</module>
> -          <module>UI</module>
>   why is this showing up as an addition?

In features.md:

> +###Basic Http Monitoring###
> - Hygieia Monitoring widget now supports basic http monitoring.
> - 
> - 
> - To use this feature use the CapOne template. The widget is very simple to configure, you just need to add the url of the services you need to monitor in the format and provide a friendly name to it.
> - The widget also supports listing dependent services and monitoring them. So if a dependent services is already configured on a another dashboard you can just declare them as dependent services.
> - 
> - `http://samplewebsite.com or https://samplewebsite.com`
> - 
> - Please do remember that if you are using a self signed certificate you would run into following error
> - 
> - `2016-11-14 17:08:25,452 ERROR c.c.d.service.ServiceServiceImpl - https://abc1234.com failed with sun.security.validator.ValidatorException: PKIX path building failed: sun.security.provider.certpath.SunCertPathBuilderException: unable to find valid certification path to requested target`
> - 
> - to resolve this please import the certificate into the JVM running your api using java keytool. 
> - 
> - Also at this time, the monitoring widget does not supports any proxy configuration.
>   Why not? Setting up proxy config is pretty straight forward
 amitmawkin

column2:
My company uses Jira with four different states: Blocked, To Do, In Progress, and Done. 
With the way that the feature widget is implemented, there are a lot of changes that must be made to display all 4 queues. Has anyone made modifications like this?
column5: Customizable States for Feature / Jira Widget
column12:
259968101 Internally jira has 3 non-modifiable categories: open, in progress, and done. This is the way jira works. Versionone appears to be the same. Your company must of mapped "blocked" to one of those types. The existing feature widget / collectors are modeled around this assumption so adding a fourth category would be a large change.
 MarkRx

column2:
In Pipeline Health Trends we find Arrows(Up & Down) followed by percentage values. Could you please explain the purpose of Up and Down arrows and it's colors.

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/835620/20137524/fe78a16c-a6a0-11e6-8f35-619da19fcc53.png)
column5: explain the purpose of Pipeline Health Trends Up or Down arrows
column12:
260465909 The arrows are for showing trend. Up is going high. Down is going low. Some UPs are bad and hence colored red. Some DOWNs are good and hence colored green..
Green = good. Red = bad. Up = trending up in value (% or count etc). Down = trending down.

column2:
**Bug Fixes:**

- Removed unused code/commented code
- Now filter by collector id when retrieving collectors
- Actually use branch provided by user
- Removed unused application settings 
- Set number of changes on a commit to 1 instead of 159753
- Utilized rest operations class instead of building an Http request 

**Enhancements:**

- Not utilizes Gitlab host set in application properties
- Extracted Url Building logic into a utility class
- Extracted building of Commit object from json string into a mapper class
- Limit number of commits returned to last 14 days
- Utilized clean method from github collector instead of just wiping everything out each time
- Get commits for branch instead of all
- Can now choose branch from UI instead of props file
- Utilize Spring URI Builder to manage url building instead of string manipulation
- Added support for Gitlab's pagination
- Moved API token into the header instead of the Url
- Added ability to provide API Token for private repos
- Added Unit Tests
- Added optional settings for trusting self signed certificates

column12:
266957638 Hi @princevijayakumar It will be helpful if you would like to share the deploy widget configuration process in detail. Thank you. supremex1
271943635 @princevijayakumar  @supremex1 
a) if using Hygieia jenkins plugin, you can configure Post build actions for Jenkins job -> Configure -> Post build actions -> select Hygieia Publisher, for each Jenkins job specific to environment. This will help Hygieia plugin to push all the data to your dashboard. 
Check Publish Deployment Resulyts 
Check Deploy Start Status 
Application Name:  
Environment Name : Dev/Int/Perf/Prod/QA
Artifact Directory :  /<directory name>/
Artifact File Name Pattern : <artifactname>-<version>.jar
Atrifcat Group : details found in pom.xml
Artifact version : details found in pom.xml
b)  Up & down arrows specify the count of servers online/offline.

Hi,
I have the docker sonar collector properties configured on docker-compose.yml. How do I pull only maybe 3/4 projects of interest rather than pulling everything sonar has. Is it possible? Thanks in advance!

My docker-compose.yml:
```yaml
hygieia-sonar-codequality-collector:
  image: hygieia-sonar-codequality-collector:latest
  container_name: hygieia-sonar-codequality
  volumes:
  - ./logs:/hygieia/logs
  links:
  - mongodb:mongo
  - hygieia-api
  environment:
  - SONAR_CRON=0 0/5 * * * *
  - SONAR_URL=http://sonar.company.com/
  - SONAR_API=http://sonar.company.com/api/projects/index/
  - SONAR_USERNAME=SonarUser
  - SONAR_PASSWORD=SonarUser

column2:
The existing repository tests in the core module utilize the [flapdoodle](https://github.com/flapdoodle-oss/de.flapdoodle.embed.mongo) mongo plugin to download and run a mongodb instance when the repository unit tests are executed. To prevent a workstation from connecting to the Internet to download and "install" software, these tests have been refactored to utilize [fongo](https://github.com/fakemongo/fongo).

Fongo is an in-memory implementation of mongodb, it intercepts calls to the mongodb drivers. It is pulled down as a maven dependency, thus no runtime downloading/installation of packages.

The intention of the repository tests feels the same with this change.

Thanks!

column2:
Adds ability to configure a regular expression to indicate environments that can ignore errors. If an environment ignores errors the UI will use a gray icon instead of a red one. The deploy widget will only turn red if an environment that is not ignoring errors fails.

Use case: There are cases when we don't care if an environment is down. In a blue/green stage-active deployment we never care about the "staging" environment. Without this change the deploy widget will almost always be red (as usually no code is staged).

** Update **
Configuration is specified in the deploy widget config

Requires PR #891 

![taxsdlc666-1](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/17504314/19867131/4af8391e-9f79-11e6-8c4e-778a7c159fac.PNG)

column2: Versionone collector collects team data into ScopeOwner repository and project data into Scope repository; Jira collector, on the other hand, collects project data into both ScopeOwner and Scope repository for now. From what I understand, ScopeOwner corresponds to team and Scope corresponds to project. The feature plugin in the UI categorizes based on ScopeOwner (teams). So what is the Scope repository to be used for?
column5: Purpose of Scope repository
column12:
262038722 @pxk5958 it will still be same in UI, just separation from different widgets. if you look at how each widget is currently , scopes was one thing which based on your definition above could be different for v1 and jira, definition of scope for V1 is given here https://community.versionone.com/VersionOne_Connect/Developer_Library/Getting_Started/Platform_Concepts/Attribute_Definition_Syntax
 amitmawkin

Team now has its own collection and Scope is for project. The UI has also been cleaned up along the same lines. column2:
Pulls maven and ivy artifacts from JFrog artifactory. Can handle multiple artifactory instances At present assumes the following artifact patterns:

> - 1. Maven artifacts:
> -      [org]/[module]/[version]/[module]-[version][-classifier].[ext]
> - 2. Ivy artifacts:
> -      (a) [org]/[module]/[revision]/[type]/[artifact]-[revision](-[classifier]).[ext]
> -      (b) [org]/[module]/[revision]/ivy-[revision](-[classifier]).xml

Known Issues:
- Cannot pull in updates on artifacts when only properties are updated. This is due to a limitation on the JFrog artifactory rest API.

@pxk5958

256064213 The `mongo` shell is actually a JavaScript shell, so you can do things like:

Based on the suggestion referenced the UI readme file section in the Encryption for private repos

Following the below step have generated a secret key and updated the respective properties file. Look like this also did not help..

From module core generate a secret key.

``` bash
java -jar /core-2.0.2-SNAPSHOT.jar com.capitalone.dashboard.util.Encryption

``` properties
    key=

    Add the same key to your repo settings file.
    This is needed for the target collector to decrypt your saved repo password.
    For example, if your repo is github add the following.
    github.properties

    github.key=

column2:
Fix for #678. Backwards compatible. Adds the ability to configure a widget to interpret sprints as either kanban, scrum, or both. This is necessary since it is not possible to deduce which sprint type a project uses from the rest api. I also did some code cleanup while there. The basic issue with the current code is that it interpreted features without sprints as being KANBAN which is not true in all use cases.

Here is how it works:
In order to be considered part of the sprint the feature must not be deleted and must have an "active" sprint asset state if the sprint is set. The following logic also applies:

A feature is part of a scrum sprint if any of the following are true:
- the feature has a sprint set that has start <= now <= end and end < EOT (9999-12-31T59:59:59.999999)

A feature is part of a kanban sprint if any of the following are true:
- the feature does not have a sprint set
- the feature has a sprint set that does not have an end date
- the feature has a sprint set that has an end date >= EOT (9999-12-31T59:59:59.999999)

Note the above are mutually exclusive.

Observe how this handles all of the following use cases:
- Typical scrums (a sprint is live for X number of weeks)
- Kanban without any sprints assigned
- Kanban using a sprint without an end date
- Kanban that was set from previous code that interpretted not having a sprint set as being KANBAN (since we use EOT in the queries above)
- Scrum & Kanban (don't see how this is a real world use case but it works similar to the previous code. Kanban will interpret backlog items as being part of kanban but that issue is existing and cannot be resolved due to lack of information)
- The code in the versionone widget that interprets sprints that have an end date > some cutoff as being KANBAN. This works as it will not end up setting the sprint data which causes the feature to be interpreted as kanban

@amp5208 @tabladrum
column5: Fix for feature widget not correctly handling some sprint type use cases - #678

column12:
254196740 I see a TimeoutException and seeing that you have over 1000 projects I would image there are a lot of user stories. 

Here are a few things you could try:
- Double check this property. It should be a string despite its name. It needs to be renamed:
  > feature.jiraIssueTypeId=Story
- Decrease the page size
- See if you can get a response using http REST. Example: 
  > curl -u username:password "https://jira.instance.com/rest/api/2/search?jql=updatedDate%3E%3D%272016-08-01%2019%3A23%27%20AND%20issueType%3D%27Story%27%20ORDER%20BY%20updated%20ASC&fields=*all%2C-comment%2C-watches%2C-worklog%2C-votes%2C-reporter%2C-creator%2C-attachment&maxResults=200&startAt=0"
- See if someone could do some database turning in jira to improve query response time
- Check for network issues
 MarkRx
254208227 @oshingc @MarkRx  
Another suggestion for 
org.apache.http.nio.reactor.ssl.SSLIOSession.receiveEncryptedData(SSLIOSession.java:340) ~

Is your jira using a self-signed SSL cert ? Check if your logs have any SSL cert exceptions. Try starting up the jira collector with -Djavax.net.ssl.trustStore=<yourtruststore> where <yourtruststore> is file containing the public key of your cert.
Refer https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/335

column5: Cannot access api from UI
column12:
252785510 @preetcam 
For the UI module set the proxypass directive in apache to point to wherever your api module is running.

ProxyPass /api http://localhost:8080/api

To find out where the api module is running ...
If you have logging set, you should see something like the following line when the api module is started up.
2016-10-07 15:20:29,037 INFO  o.s.b.c.e.t.TomcatEmbeddedServletContainer - Tomcat initialized with port(s): 8080 (http)

The above line will tell you the port number that the api runs on. Test it with the ping api..
http://localhost:8080/api/ping

column2:
This change allows the deployment widgets to handle more than one server. It has a configuration that can be set to allow this.

Use case: We have multiple deployment servers that are split up by function. One handles prod and prod-like environments. The other handles test, qa, and dev environments. Data gathered from multiple servers needs to be correlated together and treated as one application.

Changes:
- API now supports multiple deployment collectors per a single dashboard
- UI has ability to correlate applications together by ID (when enabled) thus allowing multiple deployment collector items to be used under the hood.
- Add API + UI configurable options ( #890 )

Changes will work with existing documents in the database.
