column2:
Is there a place where global system configurations live? The UI has the ability to configure themes but it doesn't seem this data is persisted.

I have a use case where I have a configuration that might effect multiple images (ui, api, and collectors). I need someplace common to store the configuration.
column5: Global configuration?
column12:
252545983 I always thought there should be a `/config` directory at the top-level of the project, which would contain all configuration for Hygieia.

There should be a `.dist` version for each config file (ex. `api.properties.dist`), which would be the "distributable" version of the configuration. You'd copy the dist version and remove the `.dist` to apply your custom configurations (ex. `api.properties`) - these would all be `.gitignore`ed.

I'd rather have all configuration in one file (`hygieia.properties`), but I'm not sure how everyone would feel about that.

Thoughts?
 mrpudn
254901779 How would that work when using docker? I wouldn't want properties to be handled at compile time.

I think for now I'm going to look into creating a rest service on the api that returns a bunch of configuration options that the UI makes use of when deciding how to render the views. The properties would be set in the api's application.properties file. The config is still static (needs to be compiled before running) but I'm not sure it would make sense for those properties that I mentioned in my use case to be dynamically configurable.
 MarkRx
254930427 Yeah configuring docker containers is a little more complicated.. like you said, ideally configuration would be done at runtime, not compile time, so that you can have a generic image with specific configuration.
 mrpudn
256093245 Threw in config skeleton as part of #891
 MarkRx
298363751 Closing. MarkRx
252279135 Examples:
- allowScmCredentials - if the UI should show the username/password fields for SCM
- allowAccountCreation - if account creation is allowed (for future LDAP hookup)
- globalTheme - the global theme
 MarkRx

column2:
This PR adds a dynamic product dashboard pipeline service that can be enabled with the feature.dynamicPipeline=enabled feature switch. This requires PR #815. More details in comment https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/804#issuecomment-247391585.

Basically data for commits, builds, deployments, and artifacts are associated dynamically using constructed composite keys. That correlated data is calculated on-demand. Doing so solves a number of synchronization issues that are pointed out below.

Data is correlated in the following ways: 
- Build -> Commit: Builds keep track of the SCM revision numbers as well as the repository and branch information (though builds with multiple repositories are not 100% accurate). Given a list of commits for the dashboard we can correlate builds to them using the scm revision number.
- EnvironmentComponent -> BinaryArtifact: Given a list of Environments we can gather DeploymentUnits and associate them to BinaryArtifacts by the component name and version number. In the future this information may be stored in metadata that is retrieved by the deployment collector. 
- BinaryArtifact -> Commit: An artifact will contain information about the HEAD svn revision number that was used to produce it. Given the scm revision number we can find it in our list of commits that are tracked for the dashboard and determine it along with all previous commits. For GIT this is done using a graph built from Commit.getScmParentRevisionNumbers(). For SVN we simply grab all revisions with a number less than ours.

This addresses the following issues
- #816 - Deploying old applications does not properly reflect in the product dashboard: only commits that come prior to the head commit for the version that was deployed are used
- #828 - Bug: Commits in the pipeline only show up in the last configured environment: since the EnvironmentComponent event listener doesn't play in to this this bug doesn't get hit
- #804 - Pipeline document not preemptively filled when created: pipeline is generated with each call
- #810 - NPE in CommitEventListener (bitbucket collector): partially fixed while I was in the code (no NPE)
- #869 - Bug: pipeline dashboard build commit time statistics off: fixed this while I was in the code
- #806 - Publishing artifacts requires build information to have already been collected: Fixed by PR #815

Sample artifact document:

```
{
    "_id" : ObjectId("57f2680746e0fb000e3026fc"),
    "_class" : "com.capitalone.dashboard.model.BinaryArtifact",
    "timestamp" : NumberLong(1475504135011),
    "artifactName" : "Helloworld",
    "canonicalName" : "Helloworld",
    "artifactGroupId" : "com.paychex.helloworld",
    "artifactVersion" : "4.9.7.20161003-101416I",
    "metadata" : {
        "jobName" : "mrichar2_helloworld",
        "scmUrl" : "https://repo.com/scm/~username/helloworld.git",
        "scmBranch" : "master",
        "buildUrl" : "http://jenkins.instance.com/job/helloworld/235/",
        "jobUrl" : "http://jenkins.instance.com/job/helloworld/",
        "buildNumber" : "235",
        "scmRevisionNumber" : "bea69104639e87faff235827e036e5021d1f93cf",
        "instanceUrl" : "http://jenkins.instance.com/"
    }
}
```

Note the following limitations / items not implemented at this time:
- Dynamic pipeline does not currently support SVN
- Date bounding is ignored as there is a current defect in the UI that shows itself here
- Only handles 1 component (though this is the same with the existing pipeline implementation)
- Jenkins branches are not 100% reliable - #857 - code currently does not filter on branch. We can get away with it for now due to commits already being filtered by branch. See comment in DynamicPipelineServiceImpl.filterBuilds for more info.
- Data doesn't display right away. This is an existing issue - #864. To work around open and close the options panel
- Jenkins commits sometimes get missed by builds. This is existing and occours with the event listener implementation as well. To work around it older commits that get skipped are added back using our best guess for a timestamp. This is a similar approach to what the BuildEventListener does
- Performance for very large datasets is not known. I don't think it will be a problem since it should be about on par with the amount of time to load team dashboards since it uses the same service calls
- Branch equality needs to be made smarter. Jenkins will use 'origin/master' whereas the user might only use 'master'

**The output we get is ERROR c.c.d.collector.DefaultGitHubClient - 401 Unauthorized:https://github.org.com/api/v3/repos/username/hello/commits?sha=master&since=2016-10-06T11:39Z**
 anchatho
251968712 @anchatho Refer to the "Encryption for private repos" section in the UI module readme.
 satishc1
255064045 Based on one of the suggestion referenced the UI readme file section in the  Encryption for private repos

Following the below step have generated a secret key and updated the respective properties file. Look like this also did not help..
1. From module core generate a secret key.
   
   ``` bash
   java -jar <path-to-jar>/core-2.0.2-SNAPSHOT.jar com.capitalone.dashboard.util.Encryption
   ```
2. Add this generated key to api.properties
   
   ``` properties
   ### api.properties
   key=<your-generated-key>
   ```
3. Add the same key to your repo settings file.
   This is needed for the target collector to decrypt your saved repo password.
   For example, if your repo is github add the following.
   
   ``` properties
   ### github.properties
   github.key=<your-generated-key>
   ```

```

column2:
Spring boot tokenization works only for properties bundles inside the spring boot jar. To cater to this and preserve backwards compatibility.
- Introduced a new file called version.properties
- File gets updated by maven during build phase with current version.
- The property value is injected in the class requiring this.

2. I haven't had time to run a test, but reviewing the files db/db-setup.js & db/db-setup.sh I think we will get errors the second time it runs if you re-create everything as the Database will already exist. > mongo --port 27037 --quiet -u superuser -p pwd

If it returns zero then the id does not exist and you should exec the id creation. (see http://stackoverflow.com/questions/12856420/mongodb-command-line-to-show-if-a-user-exists-for-puppet-unless-clause)

column5: CollectorTaskTests failing
column12:
249667571 Found it.

So the test is written to verify that save is called with the instance c one time.
`verify(baseCollectorRepository, times(1)).save(c);`

Save is called twice each with different instances. What is probably desired is checking that save is called twice using Mockito.any(Collector.class).

My failure is due to adding hashcode and equals to the BaseModel that is based on the ObjectId. When running junits the ObjectId is null so Collectors have the same hashcode and are equal. As a result it appears that save (c) is called twice since each invocation equality check works out.
 MarkRx

column2:
BuildEventListener.java is using build.getTimestamp() for the PipelineCommit timestamps. The timestamp on builds is being stamped with the system time of when the collector was run. Hence when the collector first runs and picks up a lot of builds these builds will have nearly identical timestamps. The pipeline will then report numbers based on these timestamps (when the collector ran as opposed to when the build ran).

The code should instead reference build.getStartTime() (or build.getEndTime()) to more accurately represent when the commit entered that stage of the pipeline.

Add troubleshooting section to readme to address any existing duplicate dashboard titles.

https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/812 was fixed by adding a unique index to the title field in the dashboards collection. 

But If there happen to be any duplicate titles already existing in the database, the api module will fail to launch with the following error :
Error creating bean with name 'dashboardRepository': Invocation of init method failed; nested exception is org.springframework.dao.DuplicateKeyException: Write failed with error code 11000 and error message 'null'.

This problem can be fixed by running the fixdups.js file on the mongodb instance as mentioned in the readme.

249239663 Turn up debugging by putting these in your properties file:

``` properties
logging.level.com.atlassian.jira=INFO
logging.level.com.capitalone.dashboard=DEBUG
logging.level.com.capitalone.dashboard.collector=DEBUG
```

those options are not available through docker-compose so you have to modify the command that is run and point it to a mounted properties file.

Is there more to the stack trace? What line is failing on in the hygieia code?

column12:
250471680 It does take a few minutes to get the data for the first time. From that time onwards it uses the browser cache. So depending upon how much data you already have it may take about 2 minutes for the initial load. 
 tabladrum
250485941 @tabladrum it still occurs even if the data response is very fast. I watched the response through the debugger and the data comes back in less than a second.

 sanjeevnewt
249203199 I'm not a web developer but I think some kind of refresh/notification needs to happen to the row after data is updated in product/view.js setTeamData. I suspect there is a periodic refresh of 1 minute somewhere that is causing the data to get updated but delayed by 1 refresh (so the second refresh shows the data from the 1st call, the 3rd refresh shows the data from the second call, etc).

column12:
256919007 @tabladrum lets not support multi repository, nothing good comes out of it.
 amitmawkin
256927515 I agree with @amitmawkin. I've conversed a lot with @pxk5958 and we came to the same conclusion. The "multi-repository" functionality for the git plugin is broken and unreliable. Even if it worked as intended its use case is questionable at best. The maintainers agree. They suggest using the multi-scm plugin for multiple git repos. The code changes @pxk5958 will work for multi-scm.
 MarkRx
256929748 LGTM
 amitmawkin
258135444 Ok. I am good with not supporting multi repository. Can we think of a way to put a big bold disclaimer or something? 
 tabladrum
258135869 LGTM
 tabladrum
248899364 There are few ways this might fail. One such can be this situation:
1. Setup Jenkins job with two git repo (not using MultiSCM plugin). Commit to both and you will notice that there are two back to back Jenkins builds - for each repo changes. See if your code can match the right branch.
2. If there are multiple commits in a single build, the branch refers to the top level commit. In a build with changes to multiple git repos (using Multi SCM plugin), there is no simple way to match the branch - unless we assume certain formatting to be true: origin refers to repo[0], origin1 refers to repo[1] etc.
 tabladrum
248918607 @pxk5958 could you take a look?
 MarkRx
249019343 @tabladrum Thanks. I am looking into the various cases.
 pxk5958
251985289 What we are going to do is given the branch information and the originX number we can determine the remoteUrl by pulling the job config that was used for the build and correlating the X to the X'th repo. 

It turns out that the "remoteUrls" list is buggy to begin with so this should be more reliable. I found a case where I specified multiple repositories but it ended up building one of them and claiming it built the other one.
 MarkRx
253910170 There are 2 cases to consider here.
1. Multiple repositories configured through Jenkins MultiSCM plugin. 
   In this case, each remoteUrl is in a separate action in the json response, so we just have to iterate over the actions and find the remoteUrl and corresponding branch in the lastBuiltRevision of each action. 
2. Multiple repositories configured through the 'Add repository' button on the Jenkins Git plugin.
   In this case, the remoteUrls are together in the same action and are not necessarily in the correct order to associate the remote origin, origin1, origin2,...,origin[n] with the corresponding url. There are 2 ways to go about solving this:
   (a) Parse the jenkins job config.xml and find out the remoteUrls in order. There are 2 drawbacks to this approach. If the config.xml file was changed in the time between when a job is triggered and before the queued job finally executes, we cannot get the right config.xml since we don't have the information as to when exactly the job was triggered (as opposed to when it was executed which is available in the json). The other drawback is that if the repository url is parameterized in the config, we won't have the correct url as well.
   (b) Jenkins Git plugin currently stores the remoteUrls in a HashSet which is why they are unordered. I modified it to a LinkedHashSet so that we can get them ordered and hence associate with the correct branch. I have raised an issue (https://issues.jenkins-ci.org/browse/JENKINS-38800) and have submitted a pull request with this change (https://github.com/jenkinsci/git-plugin/pull/441) but the maintainer doesn't see so far why we would need to configure multiple repositories.
   Also, like @MarkRx mentioned, sometimes the build information is wrong when multiple repositories are configured in the Git plugin, but it happens only if we change the job configuration by adding more repositories after at least 1 build has already been done. In other words, results are consistent as long as we never add more repositories after a job has been created and executed at least once.

Considering these, I think we should drop support for multiple repositories in Git plugin since it seems buggy but should support adding branch information for single repositories and MultiSCM plugin. What do you think? @tabladrum 
 pxk5958
256919007 @tabladrum lets not support multi repository, nothing good comes out of it.
 amitmawkin
256927515 I agree with @amitmawkin. I've conversed a lot with @pxk5958 and we came to the same conclusion. The "multi-repository" functionality for the git plugin is broken and unreliable. Even if it worked as intended its use case is questionable at best. The maintainers agree. They suggest using the multi-scm plugin for multiple git repos. The code changes @pxk5958 will work for multi-scm.
 MarkRx

249586861 The documentation in the docker yml file indicates that JIRA_ISSUE_TYPE_ID should be set to the ID of the User Story or Epic IssueType. However, in StoryDataClientImpl.java at line 194 it reads that value into a String issueTypeName, then compares each jira's issue type name against that ID. It never processes feature/sprint/assignee data in the loop. I found this in 2.0.2, but appears to be the same in master.
Changing line 210 to compare against issueType.getId() fixes the problem and jira data appears in the widget.
 fcostanzo-ha
249601431 The docker-compose.yml documentation is incorrect. It should be something like this:

```
 #############################################################################
 # In Jira, general IssueType IDs are associated to various "issue"
 # attributes. However, there is one attribute which this collector's
 # queries rely on that change between different instantiations of Jira.
 # Please provide a string name reference to your instance's IssueType for
 # the lowest level of Issues (e.g., "user story") specific to your Jira
 # instance.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's IssueType Name
 # listings via the following URI:  https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issuetype/
 #############################################################################
 feature.jiraIssueTypeId=Story
```

You want feature.jiraIssueTypeId=Story. The property is not named correctly.

``` bash
sudo docker run -d \
  -p 8088:80 \
  --name hygieia-ui \
  --link hygieia-api \

column2:
Jenkins collector overrides the hostname setting in application.properties and defaults to localhost. As a result it fails to connect to Jenkins host for accessing build info with api calls.

application.properties

```
# Database Name
dbname=dashboard
# Database HostName - default is localhost
dbhost=localhost
# Database Port - default is 27017
dbport=27017
# Database Username - default is blank
dbusername=dashboarduser
# Database Password - default is blank
dbpassword=dbpassword

# Collector schedule (required)
jenkins.cron=0 0/5 * * * *
jenkins.servers[0]=http://jenkinshost:8989
```

Error from collector logs below

```
2016-09-16 15:05:01,171 ERROR c.c.d.collector.DefaultHudsonClient - Client exception loading build details: I/O error on GET request for "http://localhost:8989/job/testbuild/24/api/json?tree=number,url,timestamp,duration,building,result,culprits[fullName],changeSet[items[user,author[fullName],revision,id,msg,timestamp,date,paths[file]],kind,revisions[module,revision]],actions[lastBuiltRevision[SHA1,branch[SHA1,name]],remoteUrls]":Connection refused: connect; nested exception is java.net.ConnectException: Connection refused: connect. URL =http://localhost:8989/job/testbuild/24/
```

Any clue to resolve ?
column5: Jenkins collector defaults to localhost
column12:
247925988 I am facing issues with Jenkins collector. Jenkins collector defaults to localhost always causing failures in api request to jenkin host.

Please suggest.
 bjayagop
248079517 As @jimzucker said:

> > You want to set JIRA_BASE_URL to your JIRA server

You'll have to edit your `.properties` file for the JIRA collector to point to your server
 mrpudn
250430818 How is JIRA_BASE_URL related to Jenkins collector ? The issue is in Jenkins collector and NOT in JIRA.

Pls suggest.
 bjayagop
250493719 Oh, sorry - sometimes all of this stuff just blends together, haha.

Are you running the collector in docker? It looks like there's a few things that might be the culprit
 mrpudn
277297968 @bjayagop You might be missing this --spring.config.name=jenkins while you are running the jenkins collector .. or you might have set it to hudson.  Reopen if still an issue. satishc1
247588057 You want to set JIRA_BASE_URL to your JIRA server, to get lira to work you actually want to set all of these variables to the correct value for you instance. if you are using the docker compose you can put this entry with modified values in docker-compose.override.yml.

hygieia-jira-feature-collector:
  environment:
- JIRA_BASE_URL=https://stratengllc.atlassian.net/
- JIRA_CREDENTIALS=xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
- JIRA_ISSUE_TYPE_ID=10200
- JIRA_SPRINT_DATA_FIELD_NAME=customfield_10007
- JIRA_EPIC_FIELD_NAME=customfield_10008
 jimzucker

column5: Is Email functionality can be integrated with Hygieia?
column12: 286209777 @AkhileshKJ You could do an svn post-commit hook to send an email and provide the hygieia dashboard url within it. You could add email functionality within hygieia by changing some code in the svn collector, but you would need to think about what causes the email to be triggered. satishc1

I am here stuck with some unknown issues, which is still blocking me with the finalization. As a reference I am pasting my docker file and properties-builder file:

> 
**> PROPERTIES-BUILDER**
> 				
> 				
> 				
> 				
> #!/bin/bash
> # if we are linked, use that info
> if [ "$MONGO_PORT" != "" ]; then
>   # Sample: MONGO_PORT=tcp://172.17.0.20:27017
>   export SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_HOST=`echo $MONGO_PORT|sed 's;.*://\([^:]*\):\(.*\);\1;'`
>   export SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PORT=`echo $MONGO_PORT|sed 's;.*://\([^:]*\):\(.*\);\2;'`
> fi
> 
> echo "SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_HOST: $SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_HOST"
> echo "SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PORT: $SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PORT"
> 
> 
> cat > dashboard.properties <<EOF
> #Database Name - default is test
> dbname=${SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_DATABASE:-dashboarddb}
> 
> #Database HostName - default is localhost
> dbhost=127.0.0.1
> 
> #Database Port - default is 27017
> dbport=27017
> 
> #Database Username - default is blank
> dbusername=dashboarduser
> 
> #Database Password - default is blank
> dbpassword=dbpassword
> 
> feature.dynamicPipeline=${FEATURE_DYNAMIC_PIPELINE:-disabled}
> EOF
> 
> 
> 
> 
> ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
> 
> 
**> DOCKER File**
> 
> 
> 
> FROM docker.io/java:openjdk-8-jdk
> 
> MAINTAINER Hygieia@capitalone.com
> 
> 
> ENV SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_DATABASE=dashboarddb
> ENV SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_HOST=127.0.0.1
> ENV SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PORT=27017
> ENV SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_USERNAME=dashboarduser
> ENV SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PASSWORD=dbpassword
> 
> 
> RUN \
>   mkdir /hygieia
> 
> COPY hygieia /hygieia
> COPY properties-builder.sh /hygieia/
> 
> 
> WORKDIR /hygieia
> 
> VOLUME ["/hygieia/logs"]
> 
> 
> EXPOSE 8080
> CMD sh properties-builder.sh &&\
>   java -Djava.security.egd=file:/dev/./urandom -jar api.jar --spring.config.location=C:/Abhishek/nn/Hygieia/api/dashboard.properties
>   
>   RUN sed -i -e 's/\r$//' ./properties-builder.sh


I would really appreciate your kind help in letting me know the possible reasons and the some suggestions to overcome.

Thanks and regards,
Abhishek Saxena abhishekdgenious

248199498 This might not solve your problem, but it's worth a shot 😃 

You should be able to run any module like this, too:

``` bash
mvn spring-boot:run \
  -pl <project> \
  -Dspring.config.location=<path>
# example:
mvn spring-boot:run \
  -pl collectors/build/jenkins-cucumber \
  -Dspring.config.location=config/jenkins-cucumber.properties
```

(I should probably document this somewhere haha)

I'm not really familiar with the Jenkins Cucumber collector, but if you need to pass JVM args in, you can do that with the usual `-D...` prefixed args.

column2:
A concept of "component" is used throughout Hygieia, especially in the context of deployments. For example, environment_component collection associates environment data to "components". Component.java has this:

> /**
> - A self-contained, independently deployable piece of the larger application. Each component of an application
> - has a different source repo, build job, deploy job, etc.
>   *
>   */

So here is my question: which of the two scenario's best illustrates a component?
Suppose I have an application with two parts that come from two wars: myapp-api.war and myapp-ui.war. These are deployed together. For the sake of argument suppose they are built separately and come from separate repositories.
1. **Components live at the artifact level**. They are what comes out of builds. Both myapp-api.war and myapp-ui.war are components. They happen to be deployed together.
2. **Components live at the deployment level**. They consist of a collection of artifacts. In this example my component is a deployment package that consists of myapp-api.war and myapp-ui.war. They are always deployed together.

I've been assuming that number 2 is the definition that is being used - namely tracking deployment packages as opposed to individual artifacts. However, it doesn't appear that Hygieia is setup to handle this situation the way I devised it. In particular, the product dashboard can only watch 1 artifact from 1 build that comes from 1 repository. The scenario I setup has 1 component : 2 builds : 2 repositories.
column5: Definition of "Component"?
column12: 433925402 A component is a generic place holder in Hygieia. It may or may not be tied to a single or multiple artifact. It is there just to allow future growth. tabladrum

column2: If an older version of a component is deployed it will not be reflected properly in the product dashboard. This is because the EnvironmentComponentEventListener always adds the commits from the builds from the latest artifacts. There is no logic to remove commits. Thus if an older version is deployed into an environment newer commits will still exist in the pipeline document resulting in an inaccurate dashboard.
column5: Deploying old applications does not properly reflect in the product dashboard

247392610 Please send me your contact info to my work email: tapabrata.pal@capitalone.com. I will put something on the calendar.

247000205 Here is a potential solution:
1. Artifacts need to store information about the scmRevisionNumber, scmUrl, and scmBranch that was used to create them. For a MVP we should assume an artifact comes from one repository.
2. Commits need to store information to allow a graph to be built in memory. A commit can store its parent commits (more than one for merges). A graph can be built in memory based on the HEAD information from the artifact. For scm we might be able to assume all scm revision numbers less than the one stored on the artifact are ancestors.
3. With the information from 1 and 2 determine the commits for the artifact being deployed in the environment in EnvironmentComponentEventListener. We would have to correlate the component version with the artifact version for now until a more flexible association mechanism can be devised.

column2:
Implementation of #806

Changes data model of artifacts from:

```
{
    "_id" : ObjectId("57d2c61646e0fb000d3ef42d"),
    "_class" : "com.capitalone.dashboard.model.BinaryArtifact",
    "timestamp" : NumberLong(0),
    "artifactName" : "Helloworld",
    "canonicalName" : "Helloworld",
    "artifactGroupId" : "mygroup",
    "artifactVersion" : "myversion",
    "buildInfo" : {
        "_id" : ObjectId("57d2c6014cedfd0018e051e9"),
        "collectorItemId" : ObjectId("57d15681d601800018b4e626"),
        ...
   }
}
```

to:

```
{
    "_id" : ObjectId("57d84b0346e0fb000ec42a71"),
    "_class" : "com.capitalone.dashboard.model.BinaryArtifact",
    "timestamp" : NumberLong(1473792771284),
    "artifactName" : "Helloworld",
    "canonicalName" : "Helloworld",
    "artifactGroupId" : "mygroup",
    "artifactVersion" : "myversion",
    "metadata" : {
        "jobName" : "myjob",
        "buildUrl" : "http://mybuild:8080/job/myjob/209/",
        "jobUrl" : "http://mybuild:8080/job/myjob/",
        "buildNumber" : "209",
        "instanceUrl" : "http://mybuild:8080/"
    }
}
```
- Modified /artifacts rest API endpoint slightly to accept a map of metadata
- Code that makes use of artifacts was updated to grab build information as needed by correlating jobUrl, instanceUrl, and buildNumber
- Jenkins plugin updated to work with api changes

This change allows for an independent artifact collector to be created. It also allows artifacts data to be inserted into the database before build data has been collected. Example curl to perform:

```
curl -X POST http://myapiendpoint:8080/api/artifact -H 'Content-Type: application/json' --data \
"{ \"artifactName\": \"Helloworld\", \"canonicalName\": \"Helloworld\", \"artifactGroup\": \"mygroup\", \"artifactVersion\": \"$projectVersion\", \"timestamp\": $(date +%s%3N), \"metadata\": { \"buildUrl\": \"$BUILD_URL\", \"buildNumber\" : $BUILD_NUMBER, \"jobName\": \"$JOB_NAME\", \"jobUrl\": \"$JOB_URL\", \"instanceUrl\": \"$JENKINS_URL\" } }"
```

Code added from #830:
The following metadata is now published with the jenkins plugin

scmUrl
scmBranch
scmRevisionNumber

When you do a `mvn clean install`, there are TONS of info-level and debug-level messages. Most of the time, you're really only ever looking for warn-level and error-level messages. This makes it hard to tell if anything out of the ordinary happened during a build (and it's a heck of a lot of text to try and parse through).

Even running maven in quiet-mode (i.e. `mvn clean install -q`) doesn't work completely - the source of the problem seems to stem from each application's logging configuration. Ideally, you'd give maven a command-line arg to increase the verbosity of a build (maybe only for Travis builds and if you're actually interested in info/error-level messages for something). By default, the amount of messages displayed during a build would be kept to an absolute minimum.

Thoughts?

I think I've gotten this working on a previous project just by changing configurations for logback, etc., so I could give it a shot if you guys think it's a good idea.

column2:
The current model for a Binary Artifact is:

```
{
    "_id" : ObjectId("57d2c61646e0fb000d3ef42d"),
    "_class" : "com.capitalone.dashboard.model.BinaryArtifact",
    "timestamp" : NumberLong(0),
    "artifactName" : "Helloworld",
    "canonicalName" : "Helloworld",
    "artifactGroupId" : "mygroup",
    "artifactVersion" : "myversion",
    "buildInfo" : {
        "_id" : ObjectId("57d2c6014cedfd0018e051e9"),
        "collectorItemId" : ObjectId("57d15681d601800018b4e626"),
        ...
   }
}
```

where buildInfo is a duplicate of what would exist in the build collection. At present buildInfo is populated by BinaryArtifactService by using a String representing an ObjectID that is passed in to the /artifact rest API endpoint.

This model requires a build to already exist in the database by the time artifact data is populated. It is also redundant. The result of this coupling prevents an artifact collector from being feasible as there wouldn't be a reasonable way to coordinate it with an independent build collector.

I propose that the BinaryArtifact document be changed to look something like this:

```
{
    "_id" : ObjectId("57d2c61646e0fb000d3ef42d"),
    "_class" : "com.capitalone.dashboard.model.BinaryArtifact",
    "timestamp" : NumberLong(0),
    "artifactName" : "Helloworld",
    "canonicalName" : "Helloworld",
    "artifactGroupId" : "mygroup",
    "artifactVersion" : "myversion",
    "buildData" : {
        "buildNumber" : 140
        "buildUrl" : "mybuildurl/job/etc"
   }
}
```

Code that needs to relate artifacts to builds can still do so by using buildUrl + buildNumber as a composite key to search for a unique build in the builds collection. This loosens the coupling allowing for artifact information and build information to be pulled independently of eachother. As a result an artifact collector could be created in the future (note that the artifacts would have to have metadata to associate them to builds such as artifactory properties).

column2:
Hello,

I've been looking through the code and from what I found pipeline data is dependent on 3 listeners:
- BuildEventListener
- CommitEventListener
- EnvironmentComponentEventListener

These listeners trigger on onSave events to fill in data into the relevant pipeline documents.

If a pipeline is created after data has been gathered (a collector has run many times before and for efficiency only gathers data since the last time it ran) the existing data will not exist in the pipeline. This is because the existing data is never saved after the pipeline has been created. As a result the pipeline will be missing the old data.

When a pipeline is first created it should attempt to fill in the needed data by examining existing data in the database. In order to reduce the chance of missing data due to a race condition, the pipeline should be saved first before attempting to fill in existing data. This isn't 100% fool proof in the case that the pipeline is created/filled at the same time as an event listener is run in a different collector. The only way I can think of to resolve that is to either generate pipeline data on demand (potentially expensive) or come up with some locking mechanism (potentially complicated).

Another option would be to create the pipeline document when a team is first created. Existing hygieia instances would have to be refreshed (refill data) but all instances going forward would avoid this problem since the pipeline will always exist when the collectors run. I'm not sure if this would be a problem in an environment with a lot of teams.

Example of missing data. The data was gathered in the past before the pipeline was created.
![missingdatahelloworld](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/17504314/18391059/a30d978e-767a-11e6-90bd-44af11bd3d9a.PNG)
column5: Pipeline document not preemptively filled when created

245939113 We first went with a "pipeline collector" and things didn't look clean cut. I saw the same that you saw. Will put in more details soon...
 tabladrum
247391585 Any updates? I've been thinking more the idea of the pipeline being created in a more dynamic manner.

Here are some things I am running in to:
- data can become stale and be overlooked. Example: #816 
- currently data can get lost if collectors run before the pipeline is created. Example: #804
- data may be incomplete. The SCM (commits) that are found in the build portion of the pipeline subdocument are not complete as it isn't possible to gather some information from the build collectors. The full picture of that information comes from the scm collectors. (compare DefaultHudsonClient.java addChangeSets to a commit collector to see missing data. This is because the api simply doesn't have some of the data desired).
- a failure that is later fixed may fix new data but not old data that was gathered by event listeners that contained the bug. Example: #810 
- #828

A more dynamic approach could be to gather the data as part of the api call. This would be pretty straight forward for commit and build data. For builds to gather commits and have that information be complete they would have to use the data stored about the commit to grab the complete documents in the commits collection. For environment-to-commit data this could be done in the following way:
1. Take the environment component name + version information to find the corresponding artifact (in the future this could be made better by having deployment information store the exact artifact descriptors so guessing isn't done and we are not restricted by name matches)
2. Given the artifact information (that has metadata stored about the build and head commit information) obtain the commits that exist in the artifact by following it back to the commits collection. Follow parent-child references for git or all revisions less than a revision number for scm

With the information above the same data can be returned to the UI in a more dynamic way. Doing so inherently fixes data becoming out of sync and reduces complexity in my opinion.

I can think of one potential gotcha: performance. I don't think it will be a problem as we really are not doing things that are that much different from what the team dashboards already do to collect data.

Changes that would be needed to make this work:
- artifacts need to store information about the head SCM revision they came from. Comes for free with #830
- commits need to store information about parent revision numbers (if git). Comes for free with #824
- a better way of associating environment_components to artifacts would have to be implemented. For a MVP we could use the component name and version that comes from UDeploy/XLD and associate it directly to the artifact name and version. One idea I have for the future is for putting a plugin in UDeploy/XLD that allows storing of metadata for components. That metadata could have a list of artifact group:name:version information (a list for allowing a "component" to be comprised of multiple artifacts - see #820).

Below are the relations. Yes it is a bunch of 'joins' in a no sql database but (1) that already exists in several places in the application and (2) the data is inherently relational. Note that documents cannot store sub documents of the relational data because the referenced data may not exist yet as we cannot guarantee any ordering of collectors being run. Hence any references that are followed have to be done so dynamically.
- build -> commit (build stores enough information from the jenkins build job to find the full commit details in the commit repository. This would have to be done on demand - we couldn't just store a copy of the commit details from the commit repo as we cannot guarantee any collector ordering)
- artifact -> commit (artifacts store enough information to get back to the commit)
- artifact -> build (artifacts store enough information to get back to the build)
- environment_component -> artifact (based on component name + version to artifact name + version for now. See my note above)

A penny for your thoughts?

@tabladrum @jimzucker @johnkangcurd @jayhogan 
 MarkRx

column2:
Almost all of the property generator scripts use a property named 'database' to specify what database to use. The code uses 'dbname'. Someone probably changed this property a while ago and forgot to update the property generator scripts. It has gone unnoticed because people probably have just used the default value for the database name.

This change fixes the property generator and property files to properly use 'dbname'

column2:
PR #787 renamed the database to 'dashboarddb' from 'dashboard'. This has exposed an issue with the properties generators for docker that use 'database' instead of 'dbname' as the database property name. The property generator files need to be updated to allow docker-compose to set the name of the database. Their default values should also be updated.

MongoConfig uses 
`dbname:dashboarddb`
properties-builders (except for api) use something like this:
`database=${HYGIEIA_API_ENV_SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_DATABASE:-dashboard}`

Tagging @amitmawkin
column5: Default docker values out-of-sync

column12:
245281952 MongoConfig was changed to reference dbhostport but this was missing in the api.properties file.
 satishc1
245310709 I am also getting this.

@amitmawkin could you take a look?
 MarkRx
245328831 The new code takes care of scenarios where a mongodb replica set is used instead of   single mongodb instance format being (host:port, host:port, host:port)
Also the default value of dbreplicaset is false  in the code 
   `@Value("${dbreplicaset:false}")`
the default value is false so it should not matter, and should be backwards compatible if you are not using mongodb replica set and use the old way of dbhost and dbport.
I am running some tests to see if spring needs explicitly to define the optional keys , and not the values..

PR coming from @satishc1 shortly
 amitmawkin
245387902 Fixed now.

Hi,
While trying to run the Jenkins build collector I've found that a place without proper spacing in the logs.

Example:
`2016-09-03 04:22:00,302 INFO  c.c.d.collector.CollectorTask - Error getting jobs for: http://10.100.68.2380s`

Note that the '0s' is not separated from the host at the end.
My change should make it so that there is always at least one space between the tokens.

247314111 Number estimates do not show up because your estimate fields are 0:

> "sEstimate" : "0",
> "sEstimateTime" : 0,

This can be because either your feature.jiraStoryPointsFieldName property isn't set correctly or your stories do not have story points on them.

Features in progress do not show up because your epic data is empty:

> "sEpicEndDate" : "",
> "sEpicBeginDate" : "",
> "sEpicName" : "",
> "sEpicNumber" : "",

This can be because either your feature.jiraEpicIdFieldName property isn't set correctly or your stories do not have epics assigned to them.

If these properties have since been updated you will have to trigger an update to get the data in mongo updated. You can either wipe all documents in your feature collection or go into the UI and update something in your stories.

column5: Commit details not coming into Prod
column12:
243241482 Do you have the Code Repo configured? Also, are you pushing the deployment details into Hygieia via the plugin?
 tabladrum
243406214 Thanks! I got the problem. Data issue .. But I have a bunch of questions regarding the pipeline based on my understandings -
1. If I am pushing the Artifact information using the Jenkins deployment plugin after the build is complete and incidentally that build fails. Then during the next build the change-sets of the previous failed build doesnt get reflected in the artifact information. Just to elaborate if a, b commits where in the first build and the build fails. Next time I build again and this time commit - c also comes. And an artifact is generated . The data that is published in hygieia about the artifact only includes c and not a,b. But the build has information about a and b as a result in the pipeline a and b never moves forward.
2. My build server doesn't have very old builds. But my source code repository has information some 5 months back. So in the pipeline view I am having code as old as 129 Days old which hasn't moved to build. Shouldn't we ignore so old commits data ?
3. Is there any minimum no of commits that we need before we show the stage in pipeline. For a certain pipeline I have mapped Prod and also I can see Artifacts and commits in Prod in the pipelines collection. But the Prod stage is empty. Isn't showing any data.

column2:
Bamboo collector, very similar to the Jenkins collector with minor changes
- Captures jobs under a plan and under the sub-plans based on different branches
- Cannot capture build log as it is not provided in the bamboo api

243224624 Also, can you attach some screen shots of your dashboard with Bamboo jobs? and details? Thanks for the PR. Great job.
 tabladrum
243233313 ![screen shot 2016-08-30 at 1 13 05 am](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1515614/18064874/f265ca6a-6e4e-11e6-88ca-cb3785637156.png)

![screen shot 2016-08-30 at 1 11 29 am](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1515614/18064826/c16f179a-6e4e-11e6-959d-0c5f1c22d7f0.png)

Updated the pr, please check and let me know.  Also check if the screenshots are good enough or not. Thanks!
 raynaya
243236202  This collector works just like Jenkins. The build process is a little different here. They have plans concept (equivalent to jobs) and you can have sub-plans(based on branches). This collector will find the high level plans and give you the list of high level plans available. If you select any high-level plan it will fetch all the jobs under that plan (recursively going inside sub-plans if any present based on branches ) .
 raynaya

column5: Question, were the QClasses are generated?
column12:
242234901 You can use maven to generate this classes from the core module - modern IDEs will allow you to do this from a "right click" 
 tabladrum
244396483 I found this and am hoping that we can get a more in depth answer. How does mvn know to generate this class? 
 AndrewOrr
244397689 It's Java 6 APT: See this snippet in core's pom.xml:

```
            <plugin>
                <groupId>com.mysema.maven</groupId>
                <artifactId>apt-maven-plugin</artifactId>
                <version>1.1.3</version>
                <executions>
                    <execution>
                        <goals>
                            <goal>process</goal>
                        </goals>
                        <configuration>
                            <outputDirectory>target/generated-sources/java</outputDirectory>
                            <processor>org.springframework.data.mongodb.repository.support.MongoAnnotationProcessor
                            </processor>
                        </configuration>
                    </execution>
                </executions>
            </plugin>
```
 tabladrum
244414234 Thanks for getting back to me so quickly. Will mysema look for some type of annotation to know when to build commit or any of the other q classes?
--edit: We figured it out. Thanks again.

242104026 Is this for local purposes or for hosting the dashboard for others?

column2:
Hey @tabladrum @amitmawkin, I've noticed that the list of collectors keeps growing. Would you guys like to organize them like the following?

```
/UI
/api
/core
/collectors
  /aws-cloud-collector
  /bitbucket-scm-collector
  /jenkins-build-collector
  /jenkins-cucumber-test-collector
  /jira-feature-collector
  /sonar-codequality-collector
  /subversion-scm-collector
  /udeploy-deployment-collector
  /versionone-feature-collector
  /xldeploy-deployment-collector
  ...
...
```

I've done this with another project, and it keeps these kinds of things pretty well organized and tucked away.

Granted, it's a bit of a disruptive change, as it moves a lot of stuff.

Fixes #702 
- General refactoring of the `LoginController` and `login.html` template.
- Fixed validation error in `LoginController`:
  - Basically, this line:
    
    ``` js
    $scope.lg.username.$setValidity('invalidUsernamePassword', data);
    ```
    
    This causes `lg.$valid` to always be false, which prevents the `loginData.login()` function from ever being called again.

240721989 feature.jiraIssueTypeId=Story
feature.jiraSprintDataFieldName should hold the id of the field that contains the story id. First create a sprint and assign a story to it. Then view that task with a rest call and see if you can figure out which field the assignment uses.

If you are reporting on story points your story will have to have points associated to it. If you are reporting on hours then you will need to set that up as well. In order to get "Features In Progress" to show up you must have an active story assigned to an active epic.

If your configuration was wrong you may need to update the stories / epics / tasks / sprints in jira so that they get picked up again by the collector.

column12:
241949426 Not clear on the question, are you asking whether hygieia will have any impact on your devops tools?
Hygieia dashboard does not pull data directly from your devops tools such as jenkins etc , it used collectors which runs in the background and pull data from your devops tools and store it in mongodb, which Hygieia UI access via api. Please refer to the architecture on the youtube video in README.MD file.

It's normal ?! 
Thanks.
column5: Ram memory usage
column12:
240096236 Haven't experienced this ever. 
 tabladrum
240190462 It looks like you have many instances of the API and the github collector running - am I reading that correctly? Why do you need so many to be running?
 mrpudn
240935107 Ya when you are running all collector at a time then its shows memory issue though you increase the memory size.Its because of API consumption.Make sure that you are closing all connection in collector.
perform GC if you need by looking in to JConsole. In my case I increased my RAM size and have done some connection close operation and GC. now its working fine
 sibaom
240944256 Can you execute the command line "htop" and publish the screenshot of your results to compare with my results?
 benathmane
261279068 @benathmane 
These are numbers we have gathered while running Hygieia on an m4.xlarge AWS instance with 16Gb RAM.

Red Hat Enterprise Linux Server release 7.2 (Maipo)
Linux kernel 3.10.0-327.36.1.el7.x86_64
16GB Ram

We ran the UI module inside apache httpd. The average RAM consumption was 130 Mb for apache httpd. This will go up depending on how many users hit apache. These numbers are for light usage with about 10 people running the UI.

MongoDb 3.2.9 takes up about 1 Gb RAM.

The api process takes up about 1 Gb RAM.

We have 7 collectors running with a total RAM consumption of 7Gb. This usage will go up or down depending on the cron frequency in your properties file.
jenkins-build-collector
versionone-feature-collector
subversion-collector
github-scm-collector
aws-cloud-collector
sonar-codequality-collector
jira-feature-collector
 satishc1

column2:
I'm finding the `docker-compose` script is not plug-and-play on v2.0.0. Is that expected?

Specifically this is what I'm running into:

```
$ docker-compose up
Pulling mongodb (mongo:latest)...
latest: Pulling from library/mongo
5c68a10e9f3f: Pull complete
0110f95fa9c8: Pull complete
0cba4a42bc41: Pull complete
a6eafd7fba3f: Pull complete
703d9d7e0e21: Pull complete
7a4b36461321: Pull complete
5b3580f1488d: Pull complete
913554e7fcc9: Pull complete
2f9b4a452eb8: Pull complete
Digest: sha256:e599c71179c2bbe0eab56a7809d4a8d42ddcb625b32a7a665dc35bf5d3b0f7c4
Status: Downloaded newer image for mongo:latest
Creating mongodb
Pulling hygieia-api (hygieia-api:latest)...
Pulling repository docker.io/library/hygieia-api
ERROR: Error: image library/hygieia-api not found
```

I realized this is just a small issue probably, so I tried...

``` diff
diff --git a/docker-compose.yml b/docker-compose.yml
index 78e2137..b739942 100644
--- a/docker-compose.yml
+++ b/docker-compose.yml
@@ -8,7 +8,7 @@ mongodb:
    - ./mongo:/data/db:rw
   volume_driver: local
 hygieia-api:
-  image: hygieia-api:latest
+  image: capitalone/hygieia-api:latest
   container_name: hygieia-api
   ports:
   - "8080:8080"
@@ -17,7 +17,7 @@ hygieia-api:
   links:
   - mongodb:mongo
 hygieia-ui:
-  image: hygieia-ui:latest
+  image: capitalone/hygieia-ui:latest
   container_name: hygieia-ui
   ports:
   - "8088:80"
@@ -26,7 +26,7 @@ hygieia-ui:
```

and so on. But applying this change to some of the collectors did not work. First, the `versionone` collector. I don't use that so I just commented-out. But then `jira` collector isn't working, and I'd like to use that image. It doesn't seem like `hygieia-jira-feature-collector` is on https://hub.docker.com/.

I can't build them all with `docker-compose build`, and that seems like reasonable behavior ...

```
$ docker-compose build
mongodb uses an image, skipping
hygieia-api uses an image, skipping
hygieia-ui uses an image, skipping
hygieia-jenkins-build-collector uses an image, skipping
hygieia-subversion-scm-collector uses an image, skipping
hygieia-udeploy-collector uses an image, skipping
hygieia-chat-ops-collector uses an image, skipping
hygieia-github-scm-collector uses an image, skipping
hygieia-stash-scm-collector uses an image, skipping
hygieia-jira-feature-collector uses an image, skipping
hygieia-jenkins-cucumber-test-collector uses an image, skipping
hygieia-sonar-codequality-collector uses an image, skipping
```

... since indeed the `docker-compose.yml` is set up to refer to images.

I'm just thinking, for plug-and-play demos, it would be nice to grab Hygieia and "just" run `docker-compose` :)

To that end, maybe if they all say `image:`, they should all be on DockerHub ... else, maybe they should say `build:` and refer to the Dockerfiles within this repository. Once consistent, it would be easy to add reference to this in the README or documentation, as a way for someone to get up and running quickly.

Thoughts? Happy to contribute to a solution once I know the consensus.

239480236 hmm, you probably have something in your `mongod.cfg` file that the MongoDB daemon doesn't like - I would check there for the `storage` option
 mrpudn
240095595 Can you paste the monod.cfg content?
 tabladrum
240290514 ## cfg file

systemLog:
destination: file
path: C:\dashboard\data\log\mongod.log
storage:
dbPath: C:\dashboard\data\db

## error

C:\dashboard>"C:\dashboard\mongodb\mongodb-win32-x86_64-3.2.1\bin\mongod.exe" --config "C:\dashboard\mongodb\mongod.cfg" -install
Unrecognized option: storage
try 'C:\dashboard\mongodb\mongodb-win32-x86_64-3.2.1\bin\mongod.exe --help' for more information
 sakthiom2014
240430802 Make sure the spacing is correct:

``` yaml
systemLog:
  destination: file
  path: C:\dashboard\data\log\mongod.log
storage:
  dbPath: C:\dashboard\data\db
```

Here's mine, for reference:

``` yaml
systemLog:
  destination: file
  path: /usr/local/var/log/mongodb/mongo.log
  logAppend: true
storage:
  dbPath: /usr/local/var/mongodb
net:
  bindIp: 127.0.0.1
```

Obviously, your paths will be different.
